\" style=\"text-align:center\"|Diesel engines\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''2.0 TDI CR<br />+ DPF'''||1968&nbsp;cc, [[multi-valve|16v]] [[DOHC]]<br/>[[common rail]]||[[list of Volkswagen Group diesel engines#CAGC|CAGC]]<br /><small>([[Volkswagen EA189 engine|EA189]])</small>||{{convert|88|kW|PS bhp|0|abbr=on|lk=on}}<br />at 4,000 rpm\n|{{convert|290|Nm|0|abbr=on|lk=on}}<br />at 1,750\u20132,500 rpm||10.5<br />sec.||{{convert|204|km/h|1|abbr=on}}||139||09/2009\u2013<br />2013||{{Y}}||{{Y}}||{{N}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''2.0 TDI CR<br />+ DPF'''||1968&nbsp;cc, 16v DOHC<br/>common rail||[[list of Volkswagen Group diesel engines#CAGA|CAGA]]<br /><small>(EA189)</small>||{{convert|105|kW|PS bhp|0|abbr=on}}<br />at 4,200 rpm||{{convert|320|Nm|0|abbr=on}}<br />at 1,750\u20132,500 rpm||9.2<br />sec.||{{convert|214|km/h|1|abbr=on}}||143||12/2008\u2013<br />2013||{{Y}}||{{Y}}||{{Y}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''2.0 TDI CR<br />+ DPF'''||1968&nbsp;cc, 16v DOHC<br/>common rail||[[list of Volkswagen Group diesel engines#CAHA|CAHA]]<br /><small>(EA189)</small>||{{convert|125|kW|PS bhp|0|abbr=on}}<br />at 4,200 rpm||{{convert|350|Nm|0|abbr=on}}<br />at 1,750\u20132,500 rpm||8.4<br />sec.||{{convert|229|km/h|1|abbr=on}}||153||02/2009\u2013<br />2013||{{N}}||{{Y}}||{{Y}}\n|}\n\n==Other features==\nThe Exeo also features the same multi link fully [[independent suspension|independent]] front and rear [[suspension (vehicle)|suspension]] as used on the Audi A4, again with light weight [[casting|cast]] [[aluminium alloy]] front suspension arms and virtual steering axis uprights.<ref name=AutoBlog/> All models are equipped with [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]]-supplied [[power steering]], with some models having speed sensitive '[[servotronic]]' variable assistance.<ref name=AutoBlog/><ref name=ETKA/>\n\n[[Disc brake]]s are fitted front and rear, with the radially ventilated fronts ranging in diameter from {{convert|280|mm|1}} by {{convert|22|mm|2}} thick, to {{convert|320|mm|1}} by {{convert|30|mm|2}}. At the rear are solid (un ventilated) discs ranging from {{convert|245|mm|1}} by {{convert|10|mm|2}} to {{convert|288|mm|1}} by {{convert|12|mm|2}}. All discs, front and rear, use a single piston sliding brake caliper.<ref name=ETKA/>\n\nChassis electronics feature as standard the [[Robert Bosch GmbH|Bosch]] ESP&nbsp;8.0 [[electronic stability control|Electronic Stability Programme]], which also includes [[anti-lock braking system|Anti lock Braking System]] (ABS), [[electronic brakeforce distribution|Electronic Brakeforce Distribution]] (EBD), and emergency [[Brake Assist]] (BA). This ESP system also includes [[traction control system|Anti Slip Regulation]] (ASR, or traction control), and Electronic Differential Lock (EDL) traction aids.<ref name=AutoBlog/>\n\n[[wheel|Roadwheel]] options vary from a basic 7Jx16 steel wheel with plastic wheel covers, to a number of variants of [[alloy wheel]]s, from 16\" to 18\" in diameter.<ref name=ETKA/> Conventional [[halogen lamp|halogen]] dual bulb (H7 dip and [[H1 Lamp|H1]] main) [[headlamp]]s are standard, with self leveling single source Bi [[xenon arc lamp|Xenon]] [[high-intensity discharge lamp|high-intensity discharge]] (HID) headlights<ref name=AutoBlog/> available as an option.\n\nLuggage capacity in the saloon variant, measured according to the VDA 'block' method, is {{convert|460|L|cuft|1}}.<ref name=AutoBlog/> On the other hand, in the estate Exeo ST variant, the boot size starts from {{convert|442|L|cuft|1}} (or {{convert|564|L|cuft|1}} when loaded up to roof) and after folding rear seats it rises to {{convert|882|L|cuft|1}} (or {{convert|1354|L|cuft|1}} when loaded up to roof with rear seats down).<ref>{{cite web|title=Gama Seat Exeo 2012-precios-ficha t\u00e9cnica|url=http://www.motormundial.es/gama-seat-exeo/|publisher=MotorMundial|date=29 July 2009|accessdate=|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SEAT Exeo ST. En avant le break|url=http://www.webcarcenter.com/seat/exeo/seat-exeo-st-2009.html|publisher=Webcarcenter|date=2 July 2009|accessdate=|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Sales and production figures==\nIn the year of 2009, the total annual retail sales number of SEAT Exeo cars was 21,013 vehicles (12,837 units for the Exeo and 8,176 for the Exeo ST version), while the annual production came up to 22,981 cars made in SEAT's plant in Martorell.\n\nThe total production per year of SEAT Exeo and Exeo ST cars is shown in the following table:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Model || 2008<ref name=\"SEAT Annual report 2009\">{{cite web|url=http://media.seat.com/info2010/annualreport/pantallacompleta.html |title=SEAT Annual report 2009 |publisher=SEAT |date=15 September 2010 |accessdate=15 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2009/03/GB_2008.-bin.acq/qual-BinaryStorageItem.Single.File/Y_2008_e.pdf |title=Volkswagen AG Annual Report 2008 |publisher=Volkswagen AG |date=7 April 2009 |accessdate=}}</ref> || 2009<ref name=\"SEAT Annual report 2009\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2010/03/Annual_Report_2009.-bin.acq/qual-BinaryStorageItem.Single.File/Y_2009_e.pdf |title=Volkswagen AG Annual Report 2009 |publisher=Volkswagen AG |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=}}</ref> || 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2011/03/Volkswagen_AG_Geschaeftsbericht_2010.-bin.acq/qual-BinaryStorageItem.Single.File/GB_2010_e.pdf |title=Volkswagen AG Annual Report 2010 |publisher=Volkswagen AG |date=1 March 2011 |accessdate=}}</ref> || 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://annualreport2011.volkswagenag.com/servicepages/downloads/files/entire_vw_ar11.pdf |title=Volkswagen AG Annual Report 2011 |publisher=Volkswagen AG |date=12 March 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref> || 2012<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkswagenag.com/content/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2013/03/Y_2012_e.bin.html/binarystorageitem/file/GB+2012_e.pdf |title=Volkswagen AG Annual Report 2012 |publisher=Volkswagen AG |date=14 March 2013 |access-date= |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FyTyGlS3?url=http://www.volkswagenag.com/content/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2013/03/Y_2012_e.bin.html/binarystorageitem/file/GB+2012_e.pdf |archive-date=18 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n!SEAT Exeo\n|348||13,952|| || || \n|-\n!SEAT Exeo ST\n|21||9,029|| || || \n|-\n!Total annual production || 369 || 22,981 || 23,108 || 19,559 || 10,854\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Audi A4]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|SEAT Exeo}}\n*[http://www.seat.es/content/es/brand/es/ofertas/vehiculo-nuevo/exeo-last-edition.html SEAT Exeo LAST EDITION] \u2013 SEAT ES website\n\n{{SEAT}}\n{{Modern SEAT vehicles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seat Exeo}}\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2008]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:Compact executive cars]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Station wagons]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Vehicles with CVT transmission]]\n[[Category:Flagship vehicles]]\n[[Category:Euro NCAP large family cars]]\n[[Category:SEAT vehicles|Exeo]]\n[[Category:Cars of Spain]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SEAT_Exeo"}
{"title_page": "Sonia Friedman", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Sonia Friedman\n| image         = \n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birthname     = Sonia Anne Primrose Freedman\n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1965|04}}\n| birth_place   = \n| occupation    = Theatre producer\n| spouse        = \n| yearsactive   = 1988\u2013present\n| website       = \n}}\n\n'''Sonia Anne Primrose Friedman''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (n\u00e9e '''Freedman'''; born April 1965)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://company-director-check.co.uk/director/905827447 |title=Ms Sonia Anne Primrose Friedman \u2013 free company director check. Companies House Information |publisher=Company-director-check.co.uk |date= |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> is a British [[West End Theatre|West End]] and [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] theatre producer. On 27 January 2017 Friedman was named Producer of the Year for the third year running at The Stage Awards, becoming the first person to win the award three times. In 2018, Friedman was featured in TIME100, Time Magazine's 100 Most Influential People of 2018 and was named Broadway Briefing's Show Person of the Year. In 2019, Sonia Friedman Productions ranked The Stage's most influential theatre producer in The Stage 100 2019. \n\n==Early life==\nFriedman is the youngest daughter of Clair Llewelyn Friedman (n\u00e9e Sims), a concert pianist, and the eminent Russian violinist Leonard Friedman, who was [[Concertmaster|leader]] of the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] under [[Thomas Beecham|Sir Thomas Beecham]] and co-founder of many national institutions including the [[Scottish Chamber Orchestra]] and [[Scottish Ensemble|Scottish Baroque Ensemble]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutmaria.com/timeline.html |title=Time line credits and biography \u2013 About Maria Friedman |publisher=Aboutmaria.com |date=19 March 1960 |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite interview | subject=Maria Friedman | title=Maria Friedman Q&A| interviewer=David Drake | url=http://www.broadway.com/Maria-Friedman/broadway_news/522565 | type=Interview: transcript | work=Broadway.com | date=9 December 2005 | accessdate=19 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutmaria.com/i-womanshourapril02.html |title=Radio interview Woman's Hour \u2013 About Maria Friedman |publisher=Aboutmaria.com |date=25 April 2002 |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> Her father is from a Russian Jewish immigrant family and her mother is English.<ref>{{cite news|author=Theatre Features |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-features/6878871/Sonia-Friedman-Theres-nothing-wrong-with-wearing-pretty-clothes-and-lipstick-and-still-being-a-strong-woman.html |title=Sonia Friedman: 'There's nothing wrong with wearing pretty clothes and lipstick \u2013 and still being a strong woman' |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper= |date= |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nFriedman was educated at several schools including [[St Christopher School, Letchworth]], Hertfordshire, and trained as a stage manager at the [[Central School of Speech and Drama]]. It was after organising a couple of benefits for [[World Aids Day]] during the late 1980s (one of which saw over 200 celebrities working as shop assistants in [[Covent Garden]]) that she decided to follow a career as a theatre producer.\n\n==Career==\n===Theatre producer===\nAfter working at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] between 1988 and 1993 (fulfilling the various roles of stage management, Education Manager, Head of Education and Producer of Mobile Productions and Theatre for Young People), she co-founded the new writing theatre company [[Out of Joint theatre company|Out of Joint]] in 1993 with [[Max Stafford-Clark]]. From 1998, Friedman worked as a producer for the [[Ambassador Theatre Group]]. She launched her own theatre company, Sonia Friedman Productions, in 2002. Friedman's productions have been nominated for and won numerous Olivier, Tony and other awards.{{Citation needed|date=December 2013}} At the 2014 Olivier Awards, Sonia Friedman Productions made Olivier Awards history by winning the most awards for any producer and for winning prizes for Best New Play (''[[Chimerica (play)|Chimerica]]''), Best New Musical ''([[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]''), Best Play Revival (''[[Ghosts (play)|Ghosts]]'') and Best Musical Revival (''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''). \n\nFriedman was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the 2016 Birthday Honours for services to theatre.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61608|supp=y|page=B12|date=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Friedman won producer of the year at The Stage Awards for a third year (becoming the first person to win the award three times,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2017/sonia-friedman-bags-producer-year-hat-trick-stage-awards/|title=Sonia Friedman bags producer of the year hat-trick at The Stage Awards|last=Hemley|first=Matthew|date=2017-01-27|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> and was listed as no. 1 on The Stage power list, the second solo female to hold this position in the award's history and becoming the first person to top the list that wasn't a theatre owner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2017/the-stage-100-harry-potter-producer-sonia-friedman-claims-top-spot-in-2017-theatre-power-list/|title=The Stage 100: Sonia Friedman is top of 2017 theatre power list|last=Hemley|first=Matthew|date=2017-01-05|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> \n\nSFP productions and co-productions received an unprecedented 31 nominations in the 2017 Olivier Awards \u2013 including a record-breaking 11 for [[Harry Potter and the Cursed Child]] \u2013 the most nominated new play in Olivier history. The show went on to win 9 Olivier Awards \u2013 the most ever for one production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2017/olivier-awards-2017-nominations-in-numbers/|title=Olivier Awards 2017: nominations in numbers|last=Bano|first=Tim|date=2017-03-07|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Friedman was awarded the Equity Services to Theatre Award at the 18th Annual WhatsOnStage Awards, and was featured in Time Magazine's 100 Most Influential People in the World.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/whatsonstage-awards-critical-public-vote-2018_45868.html|title=The WhatsOnStage Awards aligned with critical acclaim and it shows the West End is working {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\n===TV producer===\nIn 2015, Sonia Friedman Productions co-produced two television dramas, the BAFTA Nominated ''[[The Dresser (2015 film)|The Dresser]]'' which aired on BBC Two and directly followed after SFP's partnership with Playground Entertainment on the six-part mini-series adaptation of Hilary Mantel's 'Wolf Hall' which also aired on BBC Two in January 2015 and won two BAFTA Television Awards in 2016.\n\n==Theatre credits==\n{{Div col|colwidth=}}\n* ''[[Accidental Death of an Anarchist]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Tartuffe]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[The Queen and I (novel)|The Queen and I]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Stephen Jeffreys|The Libertine]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Shopping and Fucking]]'' (1996)\n* ''Blue Kettle / Heart's Desire'' (1997)\n* ''[[The Steward of Christendom]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Three Sisters (play)|Three Sisters]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Spoonface Steinberg]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Speed the Plow]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Noises Off]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[A Day in the Death of Joe Egg]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Benefactors (play)|Benefactors]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Up for Grabs (play)|Up For Grabs]]'' (2002)\n* ''Afterplay'' (2002)\n* ''What the Night Is For'' (2002)\n* ''[[Macbeth]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Ragtime (musical)|Ragtime]]