y Play, 2019\n* ''The Ferryman'', Sam Mendes, Outstanding Director of a Play, 2019\n* ''Harry Potter and the Cursed Child'', Outstanding New Broadway Play, 2018\n* ''Harry Potter and the Cursed Child'', John Tiffany, Outstanding Director of a Play, 2018\n* ''Harry Potter and the Cursed Child'', Christine Jones, Outstanding Scenic Design, 2018\n* ''Harry Potter and the Cursed Child'', Neil Austin, Outstanding Lighting Design, 2018\n* ''Harry Potter and the Cursed Child'', Finn Ross & Ash Woodward, Outstanding Projection Design, 2018\n* ''Harry Potter and the Cursed Child'', Gareth Fry, Outstanding Sound Design, 2018\n* ''Mean Girls'', Tina Fey, Outstanding Book of a Musical, 2018\n\n==New York Drama Critics' Circle Awards==\n* ''The Ferryman'', Best Play, 2019\n\n==Drama League Awards==\n* ''The Ferryman'', Outstanding Production of a Broadway or Off-Broadway Play, 2019\n* ''Harry Potter and the Cursed Child'', Outstanding Production of a Broadway or Off-Broadway Play, 2018\n\n== Personal life ==\nShe is the younger sister of director/actress/singer [[Maria Friedman]], violinist Richard Friedman and Dr Sarah Beecham. Her younger (half) brother, Ben, is a television director (his credits include being Director / Producer of ''[[The Great British Bake Off]]''). Sonia lives with the writer Joe Murphy in their East End pub and they have two dogs.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.soniafriedman.com/home Sonia Friedman Productions]\n* [http://www.outofjoint.co.uk/ Out of Joint Theatre]\n* {{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/may/19/theatre1|title= The Guardian profile: Sonia Friedman|publisher= The Guardian|first= Lyn|last= Gardner|date= 19 May 2006|accessdate= 15 April 2009}}\n* {{IMDb name|2300761}}\n* {{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2006/jun/24/weekend7.weekend|title= Sonia Friedman in London|publisher= The Guardian|date= 24 June 2006|accessdate= 15 April 2009}}\n* {{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/3623143/Backstage-controller.html|title= Backstage controller|publisher= Daily Telegraph|first= Catherine|last= Shoard|date= 31 August 2004|accessdate= 15 April 2009}}\n* [http://www.olivierawards.com/nominations/ Olivier Awards]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friedman, Sonia}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:English people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Central School of Speech and Drama]]\n[[Category:British theatre managers and producers]]\n[[Category:Women theatre managers and producers]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Christopher School, Letchworth]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Sonia Friedman\n| image         = \n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birthname     = Sonia Anne Primrose Freedman\n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1965|04}}\n| birth_place   = \n| occupation    = Theatre producer\n| spouse        = \n| yearsactive   = 1988\u2013present\n| website       = \n}}\n\n'''Sonia Anne Primrose Friedman''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (n\u00e9e '''Freedman'''; born April 1965)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://company-director-check.co.uk/director/905827447 |title=Ms Sonia Anne Primrose Friedman \u2013 free company director check. Companies House Information |publisher=Company-director-check.co.uk |date= |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> is a British [[West End Theatre|West End]] and [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] theatre producer. On 27 January 2017 Friedman was named Producer of the Year for the third year running at The Stage Awards, becoming the first person to win the award three times. In 2018, Friedman was featured in TIME100, Time Magazine's 100 Most Influential People of 2018 and was named Broadway Briefing's Show Person of the Year. In 2019, Sonia Friedman Productions ranked The Stage's most influential theatre producer in The Stage 100 2019. \n\n==Early life==\nFriedman is the youngest daughter of Clair Llewelyn Friedman (n\u00e9e Sims), a concert pianist, and the eminent Russian violinist Leonard Friedman, who was [[Concertmaster|leader]] of the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] under [[Thomas Beecham|Sir Thomas Beecham]] and co-founder of many national institutions including the [[Scottish Chamber Orchestra]] and [[Scottish Ensemble|Scottish Baroque Ensemble]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutmaria.com/timeline.html |title=Time line credits and biography \u2013 About Maria Friedman |publisher=Aboutmaria.com |date=19 March 1960 |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite interview | subject=Maria Friedman | title=Maria Friedman Q&A| interviewer=David Drake | url=http://www.broadway.com/Maria-Friedman/broadway_news/522565 | type=Interview: transcript | work=Broadway.com | date=9 December 2005 | accessdate=19 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutmaria.com/i-womanshourapril02.html |title=Radio interview Woman's Hour \u2013 About Maria Friedman |publisher=Aboutmaria.com |date=25 April 2002 |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> Her father is from a Russian Jewish immigrant family and her mother is English.<ref>{{cite news|author=Theatre Features |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-features/6878871/Sonia-Friedman-Theres-nothing-wrong-with-wearing-pretty-clothes-and-lipstick-and-still-being-a-strong-woman.html |title=Sonia Friedman: 'There's nothing wrong with wearing pretty clothes and lipstick \u2013 and still being a strong woman' |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper= |date= |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nFriedman was educated at several schools including [[St Christopher School, Letchworth]], Hertfordshire, and trained as a stage manager at the [[Central School of Speech and Drama]]. It was after organising a couple of benefits for [[World Aids Day]] during the late 1980s (one of which saw over 200 celebrities working as shop assistants in [[Covent Garden]]) that she decided to follow a career as a theatre producer.\n\n==Career==\n===Theatre producer===\nAfter working at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] between 1988 and 1993 (fulfilling the various roles of stage management, Education Manager, Head of Education and Producer of Mobile Productions and Theatre for Young People), she co-founded the new writing theatre company [[Out of Joint theatre company|Out of Joint]] in 1993 with [[Max Stafford-Clark]]. From 1998, Friedman worked as a producer for the [[Ambassador Theatre Group]]. She launched her own theatre company, Sonia Friedman Productions, in 2002. Friedman's productions have been nominated for and won numerous Olivier, Tony and other awards.{{Citation needed|date=December 2013}} At the 2014 Olivier Awards, Sonia Friedman Productions made Olivier Awards history by winning the most awards for any producer and for winning prizes for Best New Play (''[[Chimerica (play)|Chimerica]]''), Best New Musical ''([[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]''), Best Play Revival (''[[Ghosts (play)|Ghosts]]'') and Best Musical Revival (''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''). \n\nFriedman was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the 2016 Birthday Honours for services to theatre.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61608|supp=y|page=B12|date=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Friedman won producer of the year at The Stage Awards for a third year (becoming the first person to win the award three times,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2017/sonia-friedman-bags-producer-year-hat-trick-stage-awards/|title=Sonia Friedman bags producer of the year hat-trick at The Stage Awards|last=Hemley|first=Matthew|date=2017-01-27|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> and was listed as no. 1 on The Stage power list, the second solo female to hold this position in the award's history and becoming the first person to top the list that wasn't a theatre owner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2017/the-stage-100-harry-potter-producer-sonia-friedman-claims-top-spot-in-2017-theatre-power-list/|title=The Stage 100: Sonia Friedman is top of 2017 theatre power list|last=Hemley|first=Matthew|date=2017-01-05|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> \n\nSFP productions and co-productions received an unprecedented 31 nominations in the 2017 Olivier Awards \u2013 including a record-breaking 11 for [[Harry Potter and the Cursed Child]] \u2013 the most nominated new play in Olivier history. The show went on to win 9 Olivier Awards \u2013 the most ever for one production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2017/olivier-awards-2017-nominations-in-numbers/|title=Olivier Awards 2017: nominations in numbers|last=Bano|first=Tim|date=2017-03-07|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Friedman was awarded the Equity Services to Theatre Award at the 18th Annual WhatsOnStage Awards, and was featured in Time Magazine's 100 Most Influential People in the World.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/whatsonstage-awards-critical-public-vote-2018_45868.html|title=The WhatsOnStage Awards aligned with critical acclaim and it shows the West End is working {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\n===TV producer===\nIn 2015, Sonia Friedman Productions co-produced two television dramas, the BAFTA Nominated ''[[The Dresser (2015 film)|The Dresser]]'' which aired on BBC Two and directly followed after SFP's partnership with Playground Entertainment on the six-part mini-series adaptation of Hilary Mantel's 'Wolf Hall' which also aired on BBC Two in January 2015 and won two BAFTA Television Awards in 2016.\n\n==Theatre credits==\n{{Div col|colwidth=}}\n* ''