{"title_page": "David Leveaux", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = David Leveaux\n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1957|12|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Leicester]], England, United Kingdom\n}}\n'''David Leveaux''' (born 13 December 1957)<ref name=bio>this source shows 1958:[http://www.filmreference.com/film/67/David-Leveaux.html Biography] filmreference.com. Retrieved 9 May 2009</ref> is a British theatre director who has been nominated for five [[Tony Awards]] as director of both plays and musicals.<ref>[http://www.tonyawards.com/p/tonys_search \"Leveaux listing for Tony Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160831204617/http://www.tonyawards.com/p/tonys_search |date=31 August 2016 }}, tonyawards.com. Retrieved 9 May 2009</ref> He directs both in the UK, working at the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]], the [[Almeida Theatre]], and the [[Donmar Warehouse]], on Broadway, and also in Tokyo. \n\nLeveaux made his film directorial debut with ''[[The Exception]]'', which will be released by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. \n\n==Early life==\nLeveaux was born in Leicester and raised in [[Derby]] in the [[English Midlands|Midlands]], the son of a [[cardiologist]].<ref name=bio/> He read English language and literature at [[Manchester University]].<ref name=whatsonstage20030616>[http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821055523840 '20 Questions With...David Leveaux', ''WhatsOnStage.com'', 16 June 2003] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616061218/http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821055523840 |date=16 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn his early 20s, Leveaux became assistant to [[Peter Gill (playwright)|Peter Gill]] at [[Riverside Studios]].<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 /> When the Studios became bankrupt he was one of a group who occupied the building illegally to keep it running until it was reestablished legitimately.<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 /> While taking a break in New York City, he discovered [[Eugene O'Neill]]'s play, ''[[A Moon for the Misbegotten]]'', and revived it at Riverside, starring [[Frances de la Tour]] and [[Ian Bannen]]. The production transferred to the West End and Broadway (1984).<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 />\n\nSubsequently he directed ''[[Therese Raquin]]'' at [[Chichester]], ''[[Anna Christie]]'' in London and on Broadway, and ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]. At the [[Almeida Theatre]] he directed [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[No Man's Land (play)|No Man's Land]]'', ''[[Moonlight (play)|Moonlight]]'', ''[[Betrayal (play)|Betrayal]]'' and [[Neil LaBute]]'s ''The Distance From Here'' (2002).<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 /><ref>[http://www.haroldpinter.org/plays/index.shtml Listing of Pinter plays, with production details] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613203248/http://www.haroldpinter.org/plays/index.shtml |date=13 June 2011 }} haroldpinter.org. Retrieved 10 May 2009</ref>\n\nHe was Artistic Director of Theatre Project Tokyo, directing productions in Tokyo, including ''Electra'' (1995), ''Lulu'' (1999), ''Modern Noh Plays'', ''The Changeling'', ''Hedda Gabler'', and ''Two Headed Eagle''.<ref name=bio/><ref>[http://www.ntny.org/productions/jumpers/credits.htm Leveaux credits] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727133223/http://www.ntny.org/productions/jumpers/credits.htm |date=27 July 2011 }}''National Theatre New York''. Retrieved 9 May 2009</ref>\n\nHe was associate director of the [[Donmar Warehouse]], under [[Sam Mendes]]' artistic directorship. His revival of the musical ''[[Nine (musical)|Nine]]'' at Donmar in 1996 transferred to Broadway in 2003 with [[Antonio Banderas]], where he received a nomination for the Tony Award, Best Direction of a Musical and the musical itself won the Tony Award as Best Revival of a Musical. He directed ''[[Electra]]'' (1997), for which [[Zo\u00eb Wanamaker]] received an [[Olivier Award]].<ref>[http://www.albemarle-london.com/awards/AwardWinners.php?Award_Type=Laurence%20Olivier%20Awards&Year=1998 Olivier Awards, 1998] albemarle-london.com. Retrieved 9 May 2009</ref> He received the Olivier Award nomination for Best Director for his 1999 revival of Tom Stoppard's [[The Real Thing (play)|The Real Thing]]''.<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 /><ref>[http://www.albemarle-london.com/awards/AwardWinners.php?Award_Type=Laurence%20Olivier%20Awards&Year=2000 Olivier Awards, 2000] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928103733/http://www.albemarle-london.com/awards/AwardWinners.php?Award_Type=Laurence%20Olivier%20Awards&Year=2000 |date=28 September 2011 }} albemarle-london.com. Retrieved 9 May 2009</ref>\n\nIn 2003 he revived [[Tom Stoppard]]'s ''[[Jumpers (play)|Jumpers]]'' for the [[Royal National Theatre]] in London. This then toured the UK regions before eventually transferring to Broadway in 2004.<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 />\n\nHe directed ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' (2007) on Broadway, starring [[Kevin Kline]], with [[Ben Brantley]] writing in ''[[The New York Times]]'':\n<blockquote>\"Mr. Leveaux, the British director of the exquisite-looking Broadway productions of \"Nine\" and \"Jumpers,\" does pretty better than most of his peers, which is his blessing and his curse. (Even \"Fiddler on the Roof,\" in his hands, suggested a Vogue layout on Shtetl Chic.) He also has a strong sentimental streak, tempered by his aesthetic sense. He is the perfect man to bring \"Cyrano\" into the 21st century, presenting the play's flowery sensibility without making audiences feel they\u2019ve been doused in perfume.\"<ref>Brantley, Ben.[http://theater2.nytimes.com/2007/11/02/theater/reviews/02cyra.html?scp=2&sq=%22David%20Leveaux%22&st=cse Rapier Wit and a Nose for Poetry\",]''[[The New York Times]]''November 2, 2007</ref></blockquote>\n\nHe directed the first West End revival of Tom Stoppard's play ''[[Arcadia (play)|Arcadia]]'', which opened in May 2009.<ref>Lipton, Brian S.[http://www.theatermania.com/london/news/04-2009/david-leveaux-to-direct-west-end-revival-of-tom-st_18104.html \"David Leveaux to Direct West End Revival of Tom Stoppard's Arcadia\"], theatermania.com, 20 April 2009</ref>\n\n==Michael Riedel Controversy==\nIn 2005, Leveaux was in an altercation with ''New York Post'' columnist [[Michael Riedel (journalist)|Michael Riedel]] at the Manhattan restaurant and theatre hangout, Angus McIndoe. Riedel, who later admitted to being \"tipsy\", insulted Leveaux by claiming that English directors often ruin classic American musicals. While rumours circulated that Leveaux hit Riedel so hard that the columnist had to go to the emergency room, the truth is that Riedel was merely shoved to the floor and was not injured.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/05/movies/on-stage-and-off.html|title=ON STAGE AND OFF|accessdate=1 April 2012 |author=Zinoman, Jason|date= 5 March 2004|work= The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\n;Broadway\n*''[[Arcadia (play)|Arcadia]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' (2007)\n*''[[The Glass Menagerie]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Jumpers (play)|Jumpers]]'' (2004) \u2013 Tony Award nomination, Best Direction of a Play\n*''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Nine (musical)|Nine]]'' (2003) \u2013 Tony Award nomination, Best Direction of a Musical and [[Drama Desk Award]] nomination, Outstanding Director of a Musical\n*''[[Betrayal (play)|Betrayal]]'' (2000)\n*''[[The Real Thing (play)|The Real Thing]]'' (2000) \u2013 Tony Award nomination, Best Direction of a Play\n*''[[Electra]] (Sophocles)'' (1998)\n*''[[Anna Christie]]'' (1993) \u2013 Tony Award nomination, Best Direction of a Play\n*''[[A Moon for the Misbegotten]]'' (1984) \u2013 Tony Award nomination, Best Direction of a Play\n;[[Donmar Warehouse]]\n*''[[Closer (play)|Closer]]'' \u2013 2015\n*''The Real Thing'' \u2013 1999 (transferred to the [[Albery Theatre]], January 2000)\n*''Electra'' \u2013 (1997)\n*''Nine'' \u2013 (1996)\n;Almeida Theatre\n*''The Distance From Here'' \u2013 (2002)\n*''No Man's Land''  \u2013 1992 (transferred to [[Comedy Theatre]], 1993)\n*''Moonlight'' \u2013 (1993)\n*''Betrayal'' \u2013 (1991)\n;[[Duke of York's Theatre]]\n*''[[Backbeat (film)|Backbeat]]'' (2011).<ref>[http://www.atgtickets.com/2871/669/London/Duke-Of-Yorks/Backbeat-Tickets \"Official Duke of York's Theatre Website\"], ''Ambassador Theatre Group''. Retrieved 22 August 2011.</ref>\n\n;Film\n*''[[The Exception]]'' \u2013 (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IBDB name|15412}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081203173951/http://www.americantheatrewing.org/biography/detail/david_leveaux Biography as of November 2007 at American Theatre Wing]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leveaux, David}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:English theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Leicester]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = David Leveaux\n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1957|12|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Leicester]], England, United Kingdom\n}}\n'''David Leveaux''' (born 13 December 1957)<ref name=bio>this source shows 1958:[http://www.filmreference.com/film/67/David-Leveaux.html Biography] filmreference.com. Retrieved 9 May 2009</ref> is a British theatre director who has been nominated for five [[Tony Awards]] as director of both plays and musicals.<ref>[http://www.tonyawards.com/p/tonys_search \"Leveaux listing for Tony Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160831204617/http://www.tonyawards.com/p/tonys_search |date=31 August 2016 }}, tonyawards.com. Retrieved 9 May 2009</ref> He directs both in the UK, working at the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]], the [[Almeida Theatre]], and the [[Donmar Warehouse]], on Broadway, and also in Tokyo. \n\nLeveaux made his film directorial debut with ''[[The Exception]]'', which will be released by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. \n\n==Early life==\nLeveaux was born in Leicester and raised in [[Derby]] in the [[English Midlands|Midlands]], the son of a [[cardiologist]].<ref name=bio/> He read English language and literature at [[Manchester University]].<ref name=whatsonstage20030616>[http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821055523840 '20 Questions With...David Leveaux', ''WhatsOnStage.com'', 16 June 2003] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616061218/http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821055523840 |date=16 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn his early 20s, Leveaux became assistant to [[Peter Gill (playwright)|Peter Gill]] at [[Riverside Studios]].<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 /> When the Studios became bankrupt he was one of a group who occupied the building illegally to keep it running until it was reestablished legitimately.<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 /> While taking a break in New York City, he discovered [[Eugene O'Neill]]'s play, ''[[A Moon for the Misbegotten]]'', and revived it at Riverside, starring [[Frances de la Tour]] and [[Ian Bannen]]. The production transferred to the West End and Broadway (1984).<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 />\n\nSubsequently he directed ''[[Therese Raquin]]'' at [[Chichester]], ''[[Anna Christie]]'' in London and on Broadway, and ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]. At the [[Almeida Theatre]] he directed [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[No Man's Land (play)|No Man's Land]]'', ''[[Moonlight (play)|Moonlight]]'', ''[[Betrayal (play)|Betrayal]]'' and [[Neil LaBute]]'s ''The Distance From Here'' (2002).<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 /><ref>[http://www.haroldpinter.org/plays/index.shtml Listing of Pinter plays, with production details] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613203248/http://www.haroldpinter.org/plays/index.shtml |date=13 June 2011 }} haroldpinter.org. Retrieved 10 May 2009</ref>\n\nHe was Artistic Director of Theatre Project Tokyo, directing productions in Tokyo, including ''Electra'' (1995), ''Lulu'' (1999), ''Modern Noh Plays'', ''The Changeling'', ''Hedda Gabler'', and ''Two Headed Eagle''.<ref name=bio/><ref>[http://www.ntny.org/productions/jumpers/credits.htm Leveaux credits] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727133223/http://www.ntny.org/productions/jumpers/credits.htm |date=27 July 2011 }}''National Theatre New York''. Retrieved 9 May 2009</ref>\n\nHe was associate director of the [[Donmar Warehouse]], under [[Sam Mendes]]' artistic directorship. His revival of the musical ''[[Nine (musical)|Nine]]'' at Donmar in 1996 transferred to Broadway in 2003 with [[Antonio Banderas]], where he received a nomination for the Tony Award, Best Direction of a Musical and the musical itself won the Tony Award as Best Revival of a Musical. He directed ''[[Electra]]'' (1997), for which [[Zo\u00eb Wanamaker]] received an [[Olivier Award]].<ref>[http://www.albemarle-london.com/awards/AwardWinners.php?Award_Type=Laurence%20Olivier%20Awards&Year=1998 Olivier Awards, 1998] albemarle-london.com. Retrieved 9 May 2009</ref> He received the Olivier Award nomination for Best Director for his 1999 revival of Tom Stoppard's [[The Real Thing (play)|The Real Thing]]''.<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 /><ref>[http://www.albemarle-london.com/awards/AwardWinners.php?Award_Type=Laurence%20Olivier%20Awards&Year=2000 Olivier Awards, 2000] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928103733/http://www.albemarle-london.com/awards/AwardWinners.php?Award_Type=Laurence%20Olivier%20Awards&Year=2000 |date=28 September 2011 }} albemarle-london.com. Retrieved 9 May 2009</ref>\n\nIn 2003 he revived [[Tom Stoppard]]'s ''[[Jumpers]]'' for the [[Royal National Theatre]] in London. This then toured the UK regions before eventually transferring to Broadway in 2004.<ref name=whatsonstage20030616 />\n\nHe directed ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' (2007) on Broadway, starring [[Kevin Kline]], with [[Ben Brantley]] writing in ''[[The New York Times]]'':\n<blockquote>\"Mr. Leveaux, the British director of the exquisite-looking Broadway productions of \"Nine\" and \"Jumpers,\" does pretty better than most of his peers, which is his blessing and his curse. (Even \"Fiddler on the Roof,\" in his hands, suggested a Vogue layout on Shtetl Chic.) He also has a strong sentimental streak, tempered by his aesthetic sense. He is the perfect man to bring \"Cyrano\" into the 21st century, presenting the play's flowery sensibility without making audiences feel they\u2019ve been doused in perfume.\"<ref>Brantley, Ben.[http://theater2.nytimes.com/2007/11/02/theater/reviews/02cyra.html?scp=2&sq=%22David%20Leveaux%22&st=cse Rapier Wit and a Nose for Poetry\",]''[[The New York Times]]''November 2, 2007</ref></blockquote>\n\nHe directed the first West End revival of Tom Stoppard's play ''[[Arcadia (play)|Arcadia]]'', which opened in May 2009.<ref>Lipton, Brian S.[http://www.theatermania.com/london/news/04-2009/david-leveaux-to-direct-west-end-revival-of-tom-st_18104.html \"David Leveaux to Direct West End Revival of Tom Stoppard's Arcadia\"], theatermania.com, 20 April 2009</ref>\n\n==Michael Riedel Controversy==\nIn 2005, Leveaux was in an altercation with ''New York Post'' columnist [[Michael Riedel (journalist)|Michael Riedel]] at the Manhattan restaurant and theatre hangout, Angus McIndoe. Riedel, who later admitted to being \"tipsy\", insulted Leveaux by claiming that English directors often ruin classic American musicals. While rumours circulated that Leveaux hit Riedel so hard that the columnist had to go to the emergency room, the truth is that Riedel was merely shoved to the floor and was not injured.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/05/movies/on-stage-and-off.html|title=ON STAGE AND OFF|accessdate=1 April 2012 |author=Zinoman, Jason|date= 5 March 2004|work= The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\n;Broadway\n*''[[Arcadia (play)|Arcadia]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' (2007)\n*''[[The Glass Menagerie]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Jumpers]]'' (2004) \u2013 Tony Award nomination, Best Direction of a Play\n*''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Nine (musical)|Nine]]'' (2003) \u2013 Tony Award nomination, Best Direction of a Musical and [[Drama Desk Award]] nomination, Outstanding Director of a Musical\n*''[[Betrayal (play)|Betrayal]]'' (2000)\n*''[[The Real Thing (play)|The Real Thing]]'' (2000) \u2013 Tony Award nomination, Best Direction of a Play\n*''[[Electra]] (Sophocles)'' (1998)\n*''[[Anna Christie]]'' (1993) \u2013 Tony Award nomination, Best Direction of a Play\n*''[[A Moon for the Misbegotten]]'' (1984) \u2013 Tony Award nomination, Best Direction of a Play\n;[[Donmar Warehouse]]\n*''[[Closer (play)|Closer]]'' \u2013 2015\n*''The Real Thing'' \u2013 1999 (transferred to the [[Albery Theatre]], January 2000)\n*''Electra'' \u2013 (1997)\n*''Nine'' \u2013 (1996)\n;Almeida Theatre\n*''The Distance From Here'' \u2013 (2002)\n*''No Man's Land''  \u2013 1992 (transferred to [[Comedy Theatre]], 1993)\n*''Moonlight'' \u2013 (1993)\n*''Betrayal'' \u2013 (1991)\n;[[Duke of York's Theatre]]\n*''[[Backbeat (film)|Backbeat]]'' (2011).<ref>[http://www.atgtickets.com/2871/669/London/Duke-Of-Yorks/Backbeat-Tickets \"Official Duke of York's Theatre Website\"], ''Ambassador Theatre Group''. Retrieved 22 August 2011.</ref>\n\n;Film\n*''[[The Exception]]'' \u2013 (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IBDB name|15412}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081203173951/http://www.americantheatrewing.org/biography/detail/david_leveaux Biography as of November 2007 at American Theatre Wing]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leveaux, David}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:English theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Leicester]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJumper(link changed toJumpers (play); link changed toJumpers (play)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Leveaux"}
{"title_page": "Tangent half-angle substitution", "text_new": "{{short description|Change of variable for integrals involving trigonometric functions}}\n{{calculus|expanded=integral}}\n\nIn [[integral calculus]], the '''Weierstrass substitution''' is a method for evaluating integrals involving [[rational function]]s of [[trigonometric function]]s named after [[Karl Weierstrass]] (1815\u20131897).<ref>Gerald L. Bradley and Karl J. Smith, ''Calculus'', Prentice Hall, 1995, pages 462, 465, 466</ref><ref>Christof Teuscher, ''Alan Turing: Life and Legacy of a Great Thinker'', Springer, 2004, pages 105\u20136</ref><ref>James Stewart, ''Calculus: Early Transcendentals'', Brooks/Cole, Apr 1, 1991, page 436</ref> It converts a rational function involving sines and cosines of <math>\\theta</math> into an ordinary rational function of <math>t</math> by setting <math>t = \\tan (\\theta /2)</math>.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Stewart|first=James|title=Calculus: Early Transcendentals|publisher=Cengage Learning|year=2012|isbn=978-0-538-49790-9|edition=7th|location=Belmont, CA, USA|pages=493}}</ref><ref>Weisstein, Eric W. \"[https://mathworld.wolfram.com/WeierstrassSubstitution.html Weierstrass Substitution].\" From ''MathWorld''--A Wolfram Web Resource. Accessed April 1, 2020.</ref> [[Without loss of generality|No generality is lost]] by taking these to be rational functions of the sine and cosine. [[Michael Spivak]] wrote, that \"The world's sneakiest substitution is undoubtedly\" this technique.<ref>Michael Spivak, ''Calculus'', [[Cambridge University Press]], 2006, pages 382\u2013383.</ref>\n\n== The substitution ==\n[[File:WeierstrassSubstitution.svg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:WeierstrassSubstitution.svg|right|thumb|400x400px|The Weierstrass substitution illustrated as [[stereographic projection]] of the circle.]]\nStarting with a rational function of sines and cosines, one replaces <math>\\sin x</math> and <math>\\cos x</math> with rational functions of the variable&nbsp;<math>t</math> and relates the differentials <math>dx</math> and <math>dt</math> as follows.\n\nLet <math>t = \\tan (x/2)</math>, where <math>- \\pi < x < \\pi</math>. Then<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>James Stewart, ''Calculus: Early Transcendentals'', Brooks/Cole, 1991, page 439</ref> \n\n:<math>\\sin \\left( \\frac x 2 \\right)= \\frac t {\\sqrt{1+ t^2}} \\qquad \\text{and} \\qquad\n\\cos \\left( \\frac x 2 \\right)= \\frac 1 {\\sqrt{1+ t^2}}.</math>\n\nHence,\n\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\sin x &= \\frac{2t}{1 + t^2}, \\\\[6pt]\n\\cos x &= \\frac{1 - t^2}{1 + t^2}, \\text{and} \\\\[6pt]\ndx &= \\frac{2}{1 + t^2}\\,dt.\n\\end{align}</math>\n\n=== Derivation of the formulas ===\n[[File:Weierstrass substitution.png|thumb|right|400px|The Weierstrass substitution relates an angle to the slope of a line.]]\nLet\n\n:<math>t = \\tan\\frac{x}{2}=\\frac{\\sin\\frac{x}{2}}{\\cos\\frac{x}{2}}.</math>\n\nBy the [[double-angle formula]] and [[Pythagorean identity]], one has\n\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\sin x &=\\frac{2\\sin\\frac{x}{2}\\cos\\frac{x}{2}}{\\sin^2\\frac{x}{2}+\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}} \\\\[6pt]\n\\cos x &=\\frac{\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}-\\sin^2\\frac{x}{2}}{\\sin^2\\frac{x}{2}+\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}}.\n\\end{align}</math>\n\nOne gets \n\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\sin x &=\\frac{2t}{1+t^2}\\\\\n\\cos x &=\\frac{1-t^2}{1+t^2}\n\\end{align}</math>\n\nby dividing both numerators and denominators by <math>\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}.</math>\n\nThe equality\n\n:<math>dx = \\frac{2}{1+t^2}\\,dt,</math>\n\nresults from the following computation: \n\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dt}{dx} &= \\frac d{dx}\\,\\frac{\\sin\\frac{x}{2}}{\\cos\\frac{x}{2}}\\\\[6pt]\n&=\\frac{\\sin^2\\frac{x}{2}+\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}}{2\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}}\\qquad\\text{by quotient rule and chain rule}\\\\[6pt]\n&= \\frac{1+t^2}{2}\\qquad\\text{by dividing each term of the numerator by }\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}\n\\end{align}</math>\n\nbecause <math>\\frac{du}{dx} = 1 \\Biggl/ \\frac{dx}{du}.</math>\n\n== Examples ==\n=== First example ===\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\int\\csc x\\,dx&=\\int\\frac{dx}{\\sin x} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\int \\left(\\frac{1 + t^2}{2t}\\right) \\left(\\frac{2}{1 + t^2}\\right)dt  & t &= \\tan\\frac{x}{2} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\int\\frac{dt}{t} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\ln |t |+ C \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\ln \\left|\\tan\\frac{x}{2} \\right| + C.\n\\end{align}</math>\n\n=== Second example: a definite integral ===\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^{2\\pi}\\frac{dx}{2+\\cos x}\n&= \\int_0^\\pi \\frac{dx}{2+\\cos x} + \\int_\\pi^{2\\pi} \\frac{dx}{2+\\cos x} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\int_0^\\infty \\frac{2\\,dt}{3 + t^2} + \\int_{-\\infty}^0 \\frac{2\\,dt}{3 + t^2} & t &= \\tan\\frac{x}{2} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty \\frac{2\\,dt}{3+t^2} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\frac{2}{\\sqrt 3}\\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty \\frac{du}{1+u^2} & t &= u\\sqrt 3 \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\frac{2\\pi}{\\sqrt 3}.\n\\end{align}</math>\n\nIn the first line, one does not simply substitute <math>t=0</math> for both [[limits of integration]]. The [[Mathematical singularity|singularity]] (in this case, a [[Asymptote#Vertical asymptotes|vertical asymptote]]) of <math>t=\\tan\\frac{x}{2}</math> at <math>x=\\pi</math> must be taken into account. Alternatively, first evaluate the indefinite integral then apply the boundary values.\n\n===Third example===\n: <math>\\begin{align} \\int \\frac{dx}{a\\cos x + b\\sin x +c} &= \\int \\frac{2dt}{a(1-t^2) + 2bt + c(t^2+1)} \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\int \\frac{2dt}{(c-a)t^2 +2bt+a+c} \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\frac{2}{\\sqrt{c^2-(a^2+b^2)}} \\arctan \\frac{(c-a)\\tan \\frac{x}{2} + b}{\\sqrt{c^2-(a^2+b^2)}} + C\n\\end{align} </math>\nIf <math> 4E = 4(c-a)(c+a) - (2b)^2 = 4(c^2-(a^2+b^2))>0.</math>\n\n== Geometry ==\n[[File:Weierstrass.substitution.svg|400px|thumb|right|The Weierstrass substitution parametrizes the [[unit circle]] centered at&nbsp;(0,&nbsp;0).  Instead of +&infin; and &minus;&infin;, we have only one &infin;, at both ends of the real line.  That is often appropriate when dealing with rational functions and with trigonometric functions.  (This is the [[one-point compactification]] of the line.)]]\n\nAs ''x'' varies, the point (cos&nbsp;''x'',&nbsp;sin&nbsp;''x'') winds repeatedly around the [[unit circle]] centered at&nbsp;(0,&nbsp;0).  The point\n\n:<math>\\left(\\frac{1-t^2}{1+t^2}, \\frac{2t}{1+t^2}\\right)</math>\n\ngoes only once around the circle as ''t'' goes from &minus;&infin; to&nbsp;+&infin;, and never reaches the point&nbsp;(&minus;1,&nbsp;0), which is approached as a limit as ''t'' approaches&nbsp;\u00b1&infin;.  As ''t'' goes from &minus;&infin; to &minus;1, the point determined by ''t'' goes through the part of the circle in the third quadrant, from (&minus;1,&nbsp;0) to&nbsp;(0,&nbsp;&minus;1).  As ''t'' goes from &minus;1 to&nbsp;0, the point follows the part of the circle in the fourth quadrant from (0,&nbsp;&minus;1) to&nbsp;(1,&nbsp;0).  As ''t'' goes from 0 to 1, the point follows the part of the circle in the first quadrant from (1,&nbsp;0) to&nbsp;(0,&nbsp;1).  Finally, as ''t'' goes from 1 to&nbsp;+&infin;, the point follows the part of the circle in the second quadrant from (0,&nbsp;1) to&nbsp;(&minus;1,&nbsp;0).\n\nHere is another geometric point of view.  Draw the unit circle, and let ''P'' be the point {{nowrap|(&minus;1, 0)}}.  A line through ''P'' (except the vertical line) is determined by its slope.  Furthermore, each of the lines (except the vertical line) intersects the unit circle in exactly two points, one of which is ''P''.  This determines a function from points on the unit circle to slopes.  The trigonometric functions determine a function from angles to points on the unit circle, and by combining these two functions we have a function from angles to slopes.\n\n==Hyperbolic functions==\n\nAs with other properties shared between the trigonometric functions and the hyperbolic functions, it is possible to use [[Tangent half-angle formula#Hyperbolic identities|hyperbolic identities]] to construct a similar form of the substitution:\n\n:<math>\\sinh x = \\frac{2t}{1 - t^2},</math>\n:<math>\\cosh x = \\frac{1 + t^2}{1 - t^2},</math>\n:<math>\\tanh x = \\frac{2t}{1 + t^2},</math>\n:<math>dx = \\frac{2}{1- t^2}\\,dt.</math>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Mathematics}}\n*[[Rational curve]]\n*[[Stereographic projection]]\n*[[Tangent half-angle formula]]\n*[[Trigonometric substitution]]\n*[[Euler substitution]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/WeierstrassSubstitutionFormulas.html Weierstrass substitution formulas] at [[PlanetMath]]\n\n[[Category:Integral calculus]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Change of variable for integrals involving trigonometric functions}}\n{{calculus|expanded=integral}}\n\nIn [[integral calculus]], the '''Weierstrass substitution''' is a method for evaluating integrals involving [[rational function]]s of [[trigonometric function]]s named after after [[Karl Weierstrass]] (1815\u20131897).<ref>Gerald L. Bradley and Karl J. Smith, ''Calculus'', Prentice Hall, 1995, pages 462, 465, 466</ref><ref>Christof Teuscher, ''Alan Turing: Life and Legacy of a Great Thinker'', Springer, 2004, pages 105\u20136</ref><ref>James Stewart, ''Calculus: Early Transcendentals'', Brooks/Cole, Apr 1, 1991, page 436</ref> It converts a rational function involving sines and cosines of <math>\\theta</math> into an ordinary rational function of <math>t</math> by setting <math>t = \\tan (\\theta /2)</math>.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Stewart|first=James|title=Calculus: Early Transcendentals|publisher=Cengage Learning|year=2012|isbn=978-0-538-49790-9|edition=7th|location=Belmont, CA, USA|pages=493}}</ref><ref>Weisstein, Eric W. \"[https://mathworld.wolfram.com/WeierstrassSubstitution.html Weierstrass Substitution].\" From ''MathWorld''--A Wolfram Web Resource. Accessed April 1, 2020.</ref> [[Without loss of generality|No generality is lost]] by taking these to be rational functions of the sine and cosine. [[Michael Spivak]] wrote, that \"The world's sneakiest substitution is undoubtedly\" this technique.<ref>Michael Spivak, ''Calculus'', [[Cambridge University Press]], 2006, pages 382\u2013383.</ref>\n\n== The substitution ==\n[[File:WeierstrassSubstitution.svg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:WeierstrassSubstitution.svg|right|thumb|400x400px|The Weierstrass substitution illustrated as [[stereographic projection]] of the circle.]]\nStarting with a rational function of sines and cosines, one replaces <math>\\sin x</math> and <math>\\cos x</math> with rational functions of the variable&nbsp;<math>t</math> and relates the differentials <math>dx</math> and <math>dt</math> as follows.\n\nLet <math>t = \\tan (x/2)</math>, where <math>- \\pi < x < \\pi</math>. Then<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>James Stewart, ''Calculus: Early Transcendentals'', Brooks/Cole, 1991, page 439</ref> \n\n:<math>\\sin \\left( \\frac x 2 \\right)= \\frac t {\\sqrt{1+ t^2}} \\qquad \\text{and} \\qquad\n\\cos \\left( \\frac x 2 \\right)= \\frac 1 {\\sqrt{1+ t^2}}.</math>\n\nHence,\n\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\sin x &= \\frac{2t}{1 + t^2}, \\\\[6pt]\n\\cos x &= \\frac{1 - t^2}{1 + t^2}, \\text{and} \\\\[6pt]\ndx &= \\frac{2}{1 + t^2}\\,dt.\n\\end{align}</math>\n\n=== Derivation of the formulas ===\n[[File:Weierstrass substitution.png|thumb|right|400px|The Weierstrass substitution relates an angle to the slope of a line.]]\nLet\n\n:<math>t = \\tan\\frac{x}{2}=\\frac{\\sin\\frac{x}{2}}{\\cos\\frac{x}{2}}.</math>\n\nBy the [[double-angle formula]] and [[Pythagorean identity]], one has\n\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\sin x &=\\frac{2\\sin\\frac{x}{2}\\cos\\frac{x}{2}}{\\sin^2\\frac{x}{2}+\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}} \\\\[6pt]\n\\cos x &=\\frac{\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}-\\sin^2\\frac{x}{2}}{\\sin^2\\frac{x}{2}+\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}}.\n\\end{align}</math>\n\nOne gets \n\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\sin x &=\\frac{2t}{1+t^2}\\\\\n\\cos x &=\\frac{1-t^2}{1+t^2}\n\\end{align}</math>\n\nby dividing both numerators and denominators by <math>\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}.</math>\n\nThe equality\n\n:<math>dx = \\frac{2}{1+t^2}\\,dt,</math>\n\nresults from the following computation: \n\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dt}{dx} &= \\frac d{dx}\\,\\frac{\\sin\\frac{x}{2}}{\\cos\\frac{x}{2}}\\\\[6pt]\n&=\\frac{\\sin^2\\frac{x}{2}+\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}}{2\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}}\\qquad\\text{by quotient rule and chain rule}\\\\[6pt]\n&= \\frac{1+t^2}{2}\\qquad\\text{by dividing each term of the numerator by }\\cos^2\\frac{x}{2}\n\\end{align}</math>\n\nbecause <math>\\frac{du}{dx} = 1 \\Biggl/ \\frac{dx}{du}.</math>\n\n== Examples ==\n=== First example ===\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\int\\csc x\\,dx&=\\int\\frac{dx}{\\sin x} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\int \\left(\\frac{1 + t^2}{2t}\\right) \\left(\\frac{2}{1 + t^2}\\right)dt  & t &= \\tan\\frac{x}{2} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\int\\frac{dt}{t} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\ln |t |+ C \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\ln \\left|\\tan\\frac{x}{2} \\right| + C.\n\\end{align}</math>\n\n=== Second example: a definite integral ===\n:<math>\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^{2\\pi}\\frac{dx}{2+\\cos x}\n&= \\int_0^\\pi \\frac{dx}{2+\\cos x} + \\int_\\pi^{2\\pi} \\frac{dx}{2+\\cos x} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\int_0^\\infty \\frac{2\\,dt}{3 + t^2} + \\int_{-\\infty}^0 \\frac{2\\,dt}{3 + t^2} & t &= \\tan\\frac{x}{2} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty \\frac{2\\,dt}{3+t^2} \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\frac{2}{\\sqrt 3}\\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty \\frac{du}{1+u^2} & t &= u\\sqrt 3 \\\\[6pt]\n&=\\frac{2\\pi}{\\sqrt 3}.\n\\end{align}</math>\n\nIn the first line, one does not simply substitute <math>t=0</math> for both [[limits of integration]]. The [[Mathematical singularity|singularity]] (in this case, a [[Asymptote#Vertical asymptotes|vertical asymptote]]) of <math>t=\\tan\\frac{x}{2}</math> at <math>x=\\pi</math> must be taken into account. Alternatively, first evaluate the indefinite integral then apply the boundary values.\n\n===Third example===\n: <math>\\begin{align} \\int \\frac{dx}{a\\cos x + b\\sin x +c} &= \\int \\frac{2dt}{a(1-t^2) + 2bt + c(t^2+1)} \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\int \\frac{2dt}{(c-a)t^2 +2bt+a+c} \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\frac{2}{\\sqrt{c^2-(a^2+b^2)}} \\arctan \\frac{(c-a)\\tan \\frac{x}{2} + b}{\\sqrt{c^2-(a^2+b^2)}} + C\n\\end{align} </math>\nIf <math> 4E = 4(c-a)(c+a) - (2b)^2 = 4(c^2-(a^2+b^2))>0.</math>\n\n== Geometry ==\n[[File:Weierstrass.substitution.svg|400px|thumb|right|The Weierstrass substitution parametrizes the [[unit circle]] centered at&nbsp;(0,&nbsp;0).  Instead of +&infin; and &minus;&infin;, we have only one &infin;, at both ends of the real line.  That is often appropriate when dealing with rational functions and with trigonometric functions.  (This is the [[one-point compactification]] of the line.)]]\n\nAs ''x'' varies, the point (cos&nbsp;''x'',&nbsp;sin&nbsp;''x'') winds repeatedly around the [[unit circle]] centered at&nbsp;(0,&nbsp;0).  The point\n\n:<math>\\left(\\frac{1-t^2}{1+t^2}, \\frac{2t}{1+t^2}\\right)</math>\n\ngoes only once around the circle as ''t'' goes from &minus;&infin; to&nbsp;+&infin;, and never reaches the point&nbsp;(&minus;1,&nbsp;0), which is approached as a limit as ''t'' approaches&nbsp;\u00b1&infin;.  As ''t'' goes from &minus;&infin; to &minus;1, the point determined by ''t'' goes through the part of the circle in the third quadrant, from (&minus;1,&nbsp;0) to&nbsp;(0,&nbsp;&minus;1).  As ''t'' goes from &minus;1 to&nbsp;0, the point follows the part of the circle in the fourth quadrant from (0,&nbsp;&minus;1) to&nbsp;(1,&nbsp;0).  As ''t'' goes from 0 to 1, the point follows the part of the circle in the first quadrant from (1,&nbsp;0) to&nbsp;(0,&nbsp;1).  Finally, as ''t'' goes from 1 to&nbsp;+&infin;, the point follows the part of the circle in the second quadrant from (0,&nbsp;1) to&nbsp;(&minus;1,&nbsp;0).\n\nHere is another geometric point of view.  Draw the unit circle, and let ''P'' be the point {{nowrap|(&minus;1, 0)}}.  A line through ''P'' (except the vertical line) is determined by its slope.  Furthermore, each of the lines (except the vertical line) intersects the unit circle in exactly two points, one of which is ''P''.  This determines a function from points on the unit circle to slopes.  The trigonometric functions determine a function from angles to points on the unit circle, and by combining these two functions we have a function from angles to slopes.\n\n==Hyperbolic functions==\n\nAs with other properties shared between the trigonometric functions and the hyperbolic functions, it is possible to use [[Tangent half-angle formula#Hyperbolic identities|hyperbolic identities]] to construct a similar form of the substitution:\n\n:<math>\\sinh x = \\frac{2t}{1 - t^2},</math>\n:<math>\\cosh x = \\frac{1 + t^2}{1 - t^2},</math>\n:<math>\\tanh x = \\frac{2t}{1 + t^2},</math>\n:<math>dx = \\frac{2}{1- t^2}\\,dt.</math>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Mathematics}}\n*[[Rational curve]]\n*[[Stereographic projection]]\n*[[Tangent half-angle formula]]\n*[[Trigonometric substitution]]\n*[[Euler substitution]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/WeierstrassSubstitutionFormulas.html Weierstrass substitution formulas] at [[PlanetMath]]\n\n[[Category:Integral calculus]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent_half-angle_substitution"}
{"title_page": "Jes\u00fas Seba", "text_new": "{{spanish name 2|Seba|Hern\u00e1ndez}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jes\u00fas Seba\n| image = Jesus Seba Wigan.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Seba in 2009\n| fullname = Jes\u00fas Seba Hern\u00e1ndez\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1974|4|11|df=y}}<ref name=\"WWW\">{{cite book|title=The Who's Who of Wigan Athletic|editor-first=Dean|editor-last=Hayes|year=2004|publisher=Breedon Books|edition=|location=|page=122|isbn=0-356-17911-7}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Zaragoza]], [[Spain]]\n| death_date =\n| currentclub =\n| height = {{height|m=1.72}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = 1989\u20131990 | youthclubs1 = Miralbueno\n| youthyears2 = 1990\u20131991 | youthclubs2 = CD Oliver\n| years1 = 1991\u20131994 | clubs1 = [[Real Zaragoza B|Zaragoza B]] | caps1 = 15 | goals1 = 4 \n| years2 = 1992\u20131995 | clubs2 = [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]] | caps2 = 18 | goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 1994\u20131995 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Villareal CF|Villarreal]] (loan) | caps3 = 21 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 1995\u20131996 | clubs4 = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] | caps4 = 21 | goals4 = 3\n| years5 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs5 = [[Real Zaragoza B|Zaragoza B]] | caps5 = 47 | goals5 = 6\n| years6 = 1997 | clubs6 = [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]] | caps6 = 1 | goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 1998\u20131999 | clubs7 = [[G.D. Chaves|Chaves]] | caps7 = 31 | goals7 = 10\n| years8 = 1999\u20132002 | clubs8 = [[C.F. Os Belenenses|Belenenses]] | caps8 = 66 | goals8 = 10\n| years9 = 2002\u20132003 | clubs9 = [[Orihuela CF|Orihuela]] | caps9 = 26 | goals9 = 2\n| years10 = 2003\u20132005 | clubs10 = [[CF Palencia|Palencia]] | caps10 = 58 | goals10 = 3\n| years11 = 2005\u20132009 | clubs11 = [[Andorra CF]] | caps11 = 94 | goals11 = 22\n| years12 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs12 = CD Oliver | caps12 = | goals12 =\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 1992\u20131993 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 3 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2002\u20132006 | nationalteam2 = [[Aragon national football team|Aragon]] <small>(non-affiliated) </small> | nationalcaps2 = 2 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1 = | managerclubs1 =\n}}\n'''Jes\u00fas Seba Hern\u00e1ndez''' (born 11 April 1974) is a Spanish retired professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played mostly as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\nMostly associated to [[Real Zaragoza]], he is also known as one of the 'Three Amigos', the collective name given to the first three Spanish footballers to play in the [[English Football League]] as he had signed with [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Zaragoza===\nSeba was born in [[Zaragoza]], [[Aragon]]. He made his professional \u2013 and [[La Liga]] \u2013 debut at the age of 18 for local [[Real Zaragoza]], in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Real Sociedad]]. He would garner praise for his early performances, ultimately leading to a call-up for the [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain under-21 team]] \u2013 notably scoring twice against [[Boldklubben Frem]] for the [[1992\u201393 UEFA Cup]] (eventually 6\u20131 aggregate win).<ref name=\"Galaxy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.elperiodicodearagon.com/noticias/noticia.asp?pkid=215748|title=Un jugador de otra galaxia|trans-title=A player from another galaxy|newspaper=[[El Peri\u00f3dico de Arag\u00f3n]]|language=Spanish|date=20 November 2005|accessdate=22 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in March 1993, Seba suffered a serious [[ankle]] tear when attempting a turn in a [[Copa del Rey]] match. The injury would stunt his development and later prove a turning point in his career, as he would figure sparingly in top flight football during the following seasons.<ref name=\"RYP\">[http://www.renaldinhos.com/2010/02/jesus-seba-hernandez.html Jes\u00fas Seba Hern\u00e1ndez]; at Renaldinhos y Pavones {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nAfter a loan in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] with [[Villarreal CF]], Seba was released by Zaragoza and moved on a [[Free transfer (association football)|free transfer]] to [[England]]'s [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]], for the start of the [[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396 campaign]].<ref>[http://www.realzaragozapedia.es/index.php/Jes%C3%BAs_Seba Jes\u00fas Seba] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107130935/http://www.realzaragozapedia.es/index.php/Jes%C3%BAs_Seba|date=7 January 2010}}; at RealZaragozaPedia {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n===Wigan Athletic===\nSeba came to Wigan as one of the 'Three Amigos', alongside [[Roberto Mart\u00ednez]] \u2013 also his teammate at Zaragoza \u2013 and [[Isidro D\u00edaz]], drafted in by new chairman [[Dave Whelan]] in the summer of 1995.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wigan_athletic/8096196.stm Wigan finally land boss Martinez]; [[BBC Sport]], 15 June 2009</ref> The signings were a real coup for an [[Football League Two|English Third Division]] club, especially considering Football League teams rarely searched for talent abroad in the mid-90s and that Seba was also an under-21 international.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/los-tres-amigos-de-wigan-1595040.html|title=Los Tres Amigos de Wigan|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|first=Owen|last=Slot|date=6 August 1995|accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> 'Jesus is a Wiganer' was an early joke at the club, and Spanish flags adorned [[Springfield Park (Wigan)|Springfield Park]] on matchdays as Spanish fever gripped the town's football supporters.<ref name=\"UW\">{{cite web|url=http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/ultimatewigan/3amigos.htm|title=The Three Amigos|publisher=Ultimate Wigan Athletic|accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/josip-skoko-long-road-to-the-top-430198.html|title=Josip Skoko: Long road to the top|newspaper=The Independent|date=30 December 2006|accessdate=20 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nSeba scored his first goal with his first touch in a pre-season [[Exhibition game|friendly]], and played his first competitive game in [[1995\u201396 in English football|the season opener]] against [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]. His first official goal arrived in his first match at home (also league), a 2\u20131 defeat of [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]].<ref name=\"WWW\"/>\n\nFollowing a series of good results, aided by a string of impressive performances from Seba, Wigan were made early favourites for the Third Division championship. Mid-season, however, he found himself on the fringes of the first team, and with their league position only 'satisfactory', [[Graham Barrow]] was sacked following a 2\u20136 loss at [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]]; [[caretaker manager]] [[Frank Lord]] reinstated the player to the first team, and oversaw a 4\u20130 win over [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] in which the latter scored twice.<ref>[http://www.wafc.co.uk/history/index.htm A history of football in Wigan]; at Wigan Athletic</ref><ref>[http://www.fanbase.com/Wigan-Athletic-FC-1995-96/schedule Wigan Athletic 1995\u201396 schedule] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200228/http://www.fanbase.com/wigan-athletic-fc-1995-96/schedule|date=3 March 2016}}; at Wigan Athletic Fanbase</ref>\n\nSeba was immediately dropped by new manager [[John Deehan]], however, and would later see his appearances limited to mainly [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] roles as he struggled to find form in the latter half of [[1996\u201397 in English football|the campaign]]. He made just two appearances, both from the bench, and played his final game for Wigan on 7 September 1996, 30 minutes against Scunthorpe.<ref name=\"UW\"/>\n\nSeba then had trials at [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]], before being allowed to leave the club by Deehan in October 1996, having started 11 times and featuring from the bench on 16 further occasions. He found it most difficult to settle of the three Spaniards, and his struggle to grasp the English language was another contributory factor in his departure.\n\n===Return to Spain / Portugal===\nSeba returned to his country and Zaragoza in the 1997 January [[transfer window]], but spent almost two years appearing for [[Real Zaragoza B|the reserve team]], only playing for the main squad during the 1\u20133 home loss to [[SD Compostela]] in the final day of [[1996\u201397 La Liga|the season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/1997/06/23/082.html|title=El Zaragoza despidi\u00f3 a su vieja guardia|trans-title=Zaragoza bade farewell to their old guard|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|first=Pablo|last=Naud\u00edn|language=Spanish|date=23 June 1997|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> He then had a four-year spell in [[Portugal]], playing for [[G.D. Chaves]] and [[C.F. Os Belenenses]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2010/08/03/desporto/noticia/internacionais-e-desconhecidos-e-este-o-retrato-dos-jogadores-espanhois-na-liga-portuguesa-1449854|title=Internacionais e desconhecidos, \u00e9 este o retrato dos jogadores espanh\u00f3is na Liga portuguesa|trans-title=Internationals and unknown, meet the Spanish players in the Portuguese League|newspaper=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]|first=Marco|last=Vaza|language=Portuguese|date=3 August 2010|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribunaexpresso.pt/mundial-2018/grupo-g/belgica/2018-07-10-Roberto-Martinez-o-discipulo-de-Confucio-a-historia-do-espanhol-forjado-em-Inglaterra-que-pode-levar-a-Belgica-ao-titulo-mundial|title=Roberto Mart\u00ednez, o disc\u00edpulo de Conf\u00facio: a hist\u00f3ria do espanhol forjado em Inglaterra que pode levar a B\u00e9lgica ao t\u00edtulo mundial|trans-title=Roberto Mart\u00ednez, Confucius' disciple: the story of the Spaniard forged in England who may lead Belgium to the world title|newspaper=[[Expresso (newspaper)|Expresso]]|last=Paralta Gomes|first=L\u00eddia|language=Portuguese|date=10 July 2018|accessdate=19 October 2018}}</ref> where a heart condition whilst with the latter put his career on hold.<ref name=\"Galaxy\"/>\n\nSeba eventually recovered, but spent his later years in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] ([[Orihuela CF]], [[CF Palencia]]) or lower \u2013 during his four-year stint at amateur [[Andorra CF]], he served as [[Captain (association football)|captain]] and was a highly popular figure.<ref name=\"RYP\"/>\n\nAfter considering retirement at the end of 2008\u201309, Seba decided to return to CD Oliver. Upon joining, he expressed his desire to finish his career at the club at which he began more than 20 years earlier.<ref name=\"RYP\"/><ref name=\"Oliver\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdoliver.com/07pasion/entrevistas/entjesusseba.htm|title=Jes\u00fas Seba: veinte a\u00f1os no es nada|trans-title=Jes\u00fas Seba: twenty years is nothing|publisher=CD Oliver|first=R.|last=Lahoz|language=Spanish|date=29 July 2009|access-date=19 February 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091017090722/http://www.cdoliver.com/07pasion/entrevistas/entjesusseba.htm|archive-date=17 October 2009|df=}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nAs well as playing three matches for the Spanish under-21s, Seba appeared twice for the [[Aragon national football team|Aragon autonomous side]], against [[Castile and Le\u00f3n autonomous football team|Castile and Le\u00f3n]] in 2002 and [[Chile national football team|Chile]] on 28 December 2006. The latter, a 1\u20130 victory, was their first fixture against a [[FIFA]]-accredited international team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sport.es/es/noticias/futbol/aragon-no-rubrica-la-fiesta-hasta-el-final-1-0-5535718|title=Arag\u00f3n no rubrica la fiesta hasta el final (1\u20130)|trans-title=Aragon do not make party official until the end (1\u20130)|newspaper=[[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]]|language=Spanish|date=28 December 2006|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSeba was married with two daughters, and his former teammates Mart\u00ednez and [[Xavi Aguado]] ranked amongst his closest friends.<ref name=\"Oliver\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|1257}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seba, Jesus}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Zaragoza]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Aragonese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza B players]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza players]]\n[[Category:Villarreal CF players]]\n[[Category:Orihuela CF players]]\n[[Category:CF Palencia footballers]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Wigan Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:G.D. Chaves players]]\n[[Category:C.F. Os Belenenses players]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Andorra]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Andorra]]\n", "text_old": "{{spanish name 2|Seba|Hern\u00e1ndez}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jes\u00fas Seba\n| image = Jesus Seba Wigan.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Seba in 2009\n| fullname = Jes\u00fas Seba Hern\u00e1ndez\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1974|4|11|df=y}}<ref name=\"WWW\">{{cite book|title=The Who's Who of Wigan Athletic|editor-first=Dean|editor-last=Hayes|year=2004|publisher=Breedon Books|edition=|location=|page=122|isbn=0-356-17911-7}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Zaragoza]], [[Spain]]\n| death_date =\n| currentclub =\n| height = {{height|m=1.72}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = 1989\u20131990 | youthclubs1 = Miralbueno\n| youthyears2 = 1990\u20131991 | youthclubs2 = CD Oliver\n| years1 = 1991\u20131994 | clubs1 = [[Real Zaragoza B|Zaragoza B]] | caps1 = 15 | goals1 = 4 \n| years2 = 1992\u20131995 | clubs2 = [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]] | caps2 = 18 | goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 1994\u20131995 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Villareal CF|Villarreal]] (loan) | caps3 = 21 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 1995\u20131996 | clubs4 = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] | caps4 = 21 | goals4 = 3\n| years5 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs5 = [[Real Zaragoza B|Zaragoza B]] | caps5 = 47 | goals5 = 6\n| years6 = 1997 | clubs6 = [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]] | caps6 = 1 | goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 1998\u20131999 | clubs7 = [[G.D. Chaves|Chaves]] | caps7 = 31 | goals7 = 10\n| years8 = 1999\u20132002 | clubs8 = [[C.F. Os Belenenses|Belenenses]] | caps8 = 66 | goals8 = 10\n| years9 = 2002\u20132003 | clubs9 = [[Orihuela CF|Orihuela]] | caps9 = 26 | goals9 = 2\n| years10 = 2003\u20132005 | clubs10 = [[CF Palencia|Palencia]] | caps10 = 58 | goals10 = 3\n| years11 = 2005\u20132009 | clubs11 = [[Andorra CF]] | caps11 = 94 | goals11 = 22\n| years12 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs12 = CD Oliver | caps12 = | goals12 =\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 1992\u20131993 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 3 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2002\u20132006 | nationalteam2 = [[Aragon national football team|Aragon]] <small>(non-affiliated) </small> | nationalcaps2 = 2 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1 = | managerclubs1 =\n}}\n'''Jes\u00fas Seba Hern\u00e1ndez''' (born 11 April 1974) is a Spanish retired professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played mostly as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\nMostly associated to [[Real Zaragoza]], he is also known as one of the 'Three Amigos', the collective name given to the first three Spanish footballers to play in the [[English Football League]] as he had signed with [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Zaragoza===\nSeba was born in [[Zaragoza]], [[Aragon]]. He made his professional \u2013 and [[La Liga]] \u2013 debut at the age of 18 for local [[Real Zaragoza]], in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Real Sociedad]]. He would garner praise for his early performances, ultimately leading to a call-up for the [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain under-21 team]] \u2013 notably scoring twice against [[Boldklubben Frem]] for the [[1992\u201393 UEFA Cup]] (eventually 6\u20131 aggregate win).<ref name=\"Galaxy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.elperiodicodearagon.com/noticias/noticia.asp?pkid=215748|title=Un jugador de otra galaxia|trans-title=A player from another galaxy|newspaper=[[El Peri\u00f3dico de Arag\u00f3n]]|language=Spanish|date=20 November 2005|accessdate=22 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in March 1993, Seba suffered a serious [[ankle]] tear when attempting a turn in a [[Copa del Rey]] match. The injury would stunt his development and later prove a turning point in his career, as he would figure sparingly in top flight football during the following seasons.<ref name=\"RYP\">[http://www.renaldinhos.com/2010/02/jesus-seba-hernandez.html Jes\u00fas Seba Hern\u00e1ndez]; at Renaldinhos y Pavones {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nAfter a loan in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] with [[Villarreal CF]], Seba was released by Zaragoza and moved on a [[Free transfer (association football)|free transfer]] to [[England]]'s [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]], for the start of the [[1995\u201396 in English football|1995\u201396 campaign]].<ref>[http://www.realzaragozapedia.es/index.php/Jes%C3%BAs_Seba Jes\u00fas Seba] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107130935/http://www.realzaragozapedia.es/index.php/Jes%C3%BAs_Seba|date=7 January 2010}}; at RealZaragozaPedia {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n===Wigan Athletic===\nSeba came to Wigan as one of the 'Three Amigos', alongside [[Roberto Mart\u00ednez]] \u2013 also his teammate at Zaragoza \u2013 and [[Isidro D\u00edaz]], drafted in by new chairman [[Dave Whelan]] in the summer of 1995.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wigan_athletic/8096196.stm Wigan finally land boss Martinez]; [[BBC Sport]], 15 June 2009</ref> The signings were a real coup for an [[Football League Two|English Third Division]] club, especially considering Football League teams rarely searched for talent abroad in the mid-90s and that Seba was also an under-21 international.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/los-tres-amigos-de-wigan-1595040.html|title=Los Tres Amigos de Wigan|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|first=Owen|last=Slot|date=6 August 1995|accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> 'Jesus is a Wiganer' was an early joke at the club, and Spanish flags adorned [[Springfield Park (Wigan)|Springfield Park]] on matchdays as Spanish fever gripped the town's football supporters.<ref name=\"UW\">{{cite web|url=http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/ultimatewigan/3amigos.htm|title=The Three Amigos|publisher=Ultimate Wigan Athletic|accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/josip-skoko-long-road-to-the-top-430198.html|title=Josip Skoko: Long road to the top|newspaper=The Independent|date=30 December 2006|accessdate=20 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nSeba scored his first goal with his first touch in a pre-season [[Exhibition game|friendly]], and played his first competitive game in [[1995\u201396 in English football|the season opener]] against [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]. His first official goal arrived in his first match at home (also league), a 2\u20131 defeat of [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]].<ref name=\"WWW\"/>\n\nFollowing a series of good results, aided by a string of impressive performances from Seba, Wigan were made early favourites for the Third Division championship. Mid-season, however, he found himself on the fringes of the first team, and with their league position only 'satisfactory', [[Graham Barrow]] was sacked following a 2\u20136 loss at [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]]; [[caretaker manager]] [[Frank Lord]] reinstated the player to the first team, and oversaw a 4\u20130 win over [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] in which the latter scored twice.<ref>[http://www.wafc.co.uk/history/index.htm A history of football in Wigan]; at Wigan Athletic</ref><ref>[http://www.fanbase.com/Wigan-Athletic-FC-1995-96/schedule Wigan Athletic 1995\u201396 schedule] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200228/http://www.fanbase.com/wigan-athletic-fc-1995-96/schedule|date=3 March 2016}}; at Wigan Athletic Fanbase</ref>\n\nSeba was immediately dropped by new manager [[John Deehan]], however, and would later see his appearances limited to mainly [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] roles as he struggled to find form in the latter half of [[1996\u201397 in English football|the campaign]]. He made just two appearances, both from the bench, and played his final game for Wigan on 7 September 1996, 30 minutes against Scunthorpe.<ref name=\"UW\"/>\n\nSeba then had trials at [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]], before being allowed to leave the club by Deehan in October 1996, having started 11 times and featuring from the bench on 16 further occasions. He found it most difficult to settle of the three Spaniards, and his struggle to grasp the English language was another contributory factor in his departure.\n\n===Return to Spain / Portugal===\nSeba returned to his country and Zaragoza in the 1997 January [[transfer window]], but spent almost two years appearing for [[Real Zaragoza B|the reserve team]], only playing for the main squad during the 1\u20133 home loss to [[SD Compostela]] in the final day of [[1996\u201397 La Liga|the season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/1997/06/23/082.html|title=El Zaragoza despidi\u00f3 a su vieja guardia|trans-title=Zaragoza bade farewell to their old guard|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|first=Pablo|last=Naud\u00edn|language=Spanish|date=23 June 1997|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> He then had a four-year spell in [[Portugal]], playing for [[G.D. Chaves]] and [[C.F. Os Belenenses]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2010/08/03/desporto/noticia/internacionais-e-desconhecidos-e-este-o-retrato-dos-jogadores-espanhois-na-liga-portuguesa-1449854|title=Internacionais e desconhecidos, \u00e9 este o retrato dos jogadores espanh\u00f3is na Liga portuguesa|trans-title=Internationals and unknown, meet the Spanish players in the Portuguese League|newspaper=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]|first=Marco|last=Vaza|language=Portuguese|date=3 August 2010|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribunaexpresso.pt/mundial-2018/grupo-g/belgica/2018-07-10-Roberto-Martinez-o-discipulo-de-Confucio-a-historia-do-espanhol-forjado-em-Inglaterra-que-pode-levar-a-Belgica-ao-titulo-mundial|title=Roberto Mart\u00ednez, o disc\u00edpulo de Conf\u00facio: a hist\u00f3ria do espanhol forjado em Inglaterra que pode levar a B\u00e9lgica ao t\u00edtulo mundial|trans-title=Roberto Mart\u00ednez, Confucius' disciple: the story of the Spaniard forged in England who may lead Belgium to the world title|newspaper=[[Expresso (newspaper)|Expresso]]|last=Paralta Gomes|first=L\u00eddia|language=Portuguese|date=10 July 2018|accessdate=19 October 2018}}</ref> where a heart condition whilst with the latter put his career on hold.<ref name=\"Galaxy\"/>\n\nSeba eventually recovered, but spent his later years in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] ([[Orihuela CF]], [[CF Palencia]]) or lower \u2013 during his four-year stint at amateur [[Andorra CF]], he served as [[Captain (association football)|captain]] and was a highly popular figure.<ref name=\"RYP\"/>\n\nAfter considering retirement at the end of 2008\u201309, Seba decided to return to CD Oliver. Upon joining, he expressed his desire to finish his career at the club at which he began more than 20 years earlier.<ref name=\"RYP\"/><ref name=\"Oliver\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdoliver.com/07pasion/entrevistas/entjesusseba.htm|title=Jes\u00fas Seba: veinte a\u00f1os no es nada|trans-title=Jes\u00fas Seba: twenty years is nothing|publisher=CD Oliver|first=R.|last=Lahoz|language=Spanish|date=29 July 2009|access-date=19 February 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091017090722/http://www.cdoliver.com/07pasion/entrevistas/entjesusseba.htm|archive-date=17 October 2009|df=}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nAs well as playing three matches for the Spanish under-21s, Seba appeared twice for the [[Aragon national football team|Aragon autonomous side]], against [[Castile and Le\u00f3n autonomous football team|Castile and Le\u00f3n]] in 2002 and [[Chile national football team|Chile]] on 28 December 2006. The latter, a 1\u20130 victory, was their first fixture against a [[FIFA]]-accredited international team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sport.es/es/noticias/futbol/aragon-no-rubrica-la-fiesta-hasta-el-final-1-0-5535718|title=Arag\u00f3n no rubrica la fiesta hasta el final (1\u20130)|trans-title=Aragon do not make party official until the end (1\u20130)|newspaper=[[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]]|language=Spanish|date=28 December 2006|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSeba was married with two daughters, and his former teammates Mart\u00ednez and [[Xavi Aguado]] ranked amongst his closest friends.<ref name=\"Oliver\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|1257}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seba, Jesus}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Zaragoza]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Aragonese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza B players]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza players]]\n[[Category:Villarreal CF players]]\n[[Category:Orihuela CF players]]\n[[Category:CF Palencia footballers]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Wigan Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:G.D. Chaves players]]\n[[Category:C.F. Os Belenenses players]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Andorra]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Andorra]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jes%C3%BAs_Seba"}
{"title_page": "1982 Women's Cricket World Cup", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox cricket tournament\n| name = 1982 Women's World Cup\n| image = 1982 Women's Cricket World Cup logo.png\n| image_size = 200px\n| fromdate = 10 January\n| todate = 7 February 1982\n| administrator = [[International Women's Cricket Council|IWCC]]\n| cricket format = [[Women's One Day International|ODI]] ([[Limited-overs cricket|60-over]])\n| tournament format = [[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]] and final\n| host = {{flag|New Zealand}}\n| champions = {{nobr|{{cr|Australia}} (2nd title)}}\n| runner up = {{crw|England}}\n| participants = 5\n| matches = 31\n| player of the series = \n| most runs = {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Jan Brittin]] (391)\n| most wickets = {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lyn Fullston]] (23)\n| website = \n| previous_year = 1978\n| previous_tournament = 1978 Women's Cricket World Cup\n| next_year = 1988\n| next_tournament = 1988 Women's Cricket World Cup\n}}\n\nThe '''1982 Hansells Vita Fresh Women's World Cup''' was an international [[cricket]] tournament played in [[New Zealand]] from 10 January to 7 February 1982. Hosted by New Zealand for the first time, it was the third edition of the [[Women's Cricket World Cup]], coming four years after the previous [[1978 Women's Cricket World Cup|1978 World Cup]] in India.\n\nThe tournament, which featured a triple [[Round-robin tournament|round-robin]], was at the time the longest World Cup in both duration and in the number of matches played. Six teams were originally invited, but the [[Netherlands women's national cricket team|Netherlands]] were unable to attend and the [[West Indies women's cricket team|West Indies]] withdrew in protest at the [[1981 South Africa rugby union tour|1981 South African rugby tour of New Zealand]]. Those teams were instead replaced by a composite [[International XI women's cricket team|International XI]] team.<ref name=\"bird\">{{cite book |last=Bird|first=Dickie|author-link=Dickie Bird|date=2012|title=My Autobiography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZfT2qjcg6PoC|chapter=11 Bowling the Maidens Over|location= |publisher=Hachette UK|page= |isbn= 1444756079}}</ref> [[Australia women's national cricket team|Australia]] did not lose a single match, winning its second consecutive tournament by defeating [[England women's cricket team|England]] in [[#Final|the final]] at [[Lancaster Park]], [[Christchurch]]. Australia's thirteen matches without defeat were part of a greater series of 24 matches without defeat, extending from 1978 to 1985, which remains an ODI record.<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/nz-1-day-2011/content/records/283102.html Records / Women's One-Day Internationals / Team records / Most consecutive matches without defeat] \u2013 ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 31 August 2015.</ref> The World Cup was marked by its low scoring, with only one team recording more than 250 runs in an innings,<ref>Daniel Grummitt (28 January 2013). [http://www.cricketworld.com/women-s-world-cup-history-new-zealand-1982/33303.htm Women's World Cup History - New Zealand 1982] \u2013 CricketWorld. Retrieved 31 August 2015.</ref> and was also notable for featuring two matches that were [[Tie (cricket)|tied]] \u2013 the first between England and New Zealand, and the second between England and Australia. They were the first ties in international women's cricket.<ref name=\"tie\">[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/nz-1-day-2011/content/records/283289.html Records / Women's One-Day Internationals / Team records / Tied matches] \u2013 ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 31 August 2015.</ref> England's [[Jan Brittin]] led the tournament in runs, while Australian spinner [[Lyn Fullston]] led the tournament in wickets.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/1/Womens_World_Cup_1977-78/Batting_by_Runs.html Batting in Hansells Vita Fresh Women's World Cup 1981/82 (ordered by runs)] \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 30 August 2015.</ref><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Hansells_Vita_Fresh_Womens_World_Cup_1981-82/Bowling_by_Wickets.html Bowling in Hansells Vita Fresh Women's World Cup 1981/82 (ordered by wickets)] \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 30 August 2015.</ref>\n\n==Background==\nProfessional [[Limited overs cricket|one-day cricket]] was first played in 1962 when four English [[county cricket]] teams filled in a gap to play in a limited overs knockout competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/510124.html |title=The low-key birth of one-day cricket |date=9 April 2011 |first=Martin |last=Williamson |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430121854/http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/510124.html |archive-date=30 April 2015 |website=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Nine years later in 1971, the first men's [[One Day International]] took place at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]] (MCG) as a replacement for the third [[Test cricket|Test]] of the [[1970\u201371 Ashes series]] between [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]] and [[England cricket team|England]], which had been abandoned due to rain. The game was a forty [[Over (cricket)|overs]] per side contest, which Australia won.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/464234.html |title=The birth of the one-day international |last=Williamson |first=Martin |website=ESPNCricinfo |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117180444/http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/464234.html |archive-date=17 November 2017 |access-date=15 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nTwo years after that, [[Jack Hayward]] and [[Rachael Heyhoe-Flint]] organised the [[1973 Women's Cricket World Cup]], predating the [[1975 Cricket World Cup|first men's Cricket World Cup]] by two years. The tournament was played as a league format; the team who topped the points table at the conclusion would be champions. [[England women's cricket team|England]] beat [[Australia national women's cricket team|Australia]] in the last match of the tournament to become the first Women's World Cup winners.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cricketworld.com/women-s-world-cup-history-1973-1978/33304.htm |title=Women's World Cup History \u2013 1973 & 1978 |website=Cricketworld |date=28 January 2013 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> The second Women's Cricket World Cup was scheduled to take place in South Africa in 1978, but with that country facing increasing [[Sporting boycott of South Africa during the apartheid era|sporting boycotts due to its apartheid policies]], and withdrawals for financial reasons by the [[Netherlands national women's cricket team|Netherlands]] and [[West Indies women's cricket team|West Indies]], the tournament was in jeopardy. The [[1978 Women's Cricket World Cup]] was belatedly relocated to India, and featured only four teams. The tournament was once again played in a league format, but as in 1973, the final group match acted as a de facto final: Australia beat England to become champions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nzcricketmuseum.co.nz/1978-womens-cricket-world-cup/ |title=The 1978 Women\u2019s Cricket World Cup |last=Bell |first=Jamie |publisher=New Zealand Cricket Museum |date=9 May 2017 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Squads==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! width=33% | {{crw|AUS}}<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Hansells_Vita_Fresh_Womens_World_Cup_1981-82/Australia_Women_Batting.html Batting and fielding for Australia women], Hansells Vita Fresh Women's World Cup 1981/82 \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 29 August 2015.</ref>\n! width=33% | {{crw|ENG}}<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Hansells_Vita_Fresh_Womens_World_Cup_1981-82/England_Women_Batting.html Batting and fielding for England women], Hansells Vita Fresh Women's World Cup 1981/82 \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 29 August 2015.</ref>\n! width=33% | {{crw|IND}}<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Hansells_Vita_Fresh_Womens_World_Cup_1981-82/India_Batting.html Batting and fielding for India women], Hansells Vita Fresh Women's World Cup 1981/82 \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 29 August 2015.</ref>\n|-\n|valign=top|\n* [[Sharon Tredrea]] ([[Captain (cricket)|c]])\n* [[Lee Albon]]\n* [[Denise Emerson|Denise Alderman]]\n* [[Marie Lutschini|Marie Cornish]]\n* [[Lyn Fullston]]\n* [[Sharyn Hill]]\n* [[Jen Jacobs]]\n* [[Jill Kennare]]\n* [[Denise Martin]]\n* [[Karen Read]]\n* [[Terri Russell]]\n* [[Raelee Thompson]]\n* [[Peta Verco]]\n* [[Christine White (cricketer)|Christine White]]\n|valign=top|\n* [[Susan Goatman]] ([[Captain (cricket)|c]])\n* [[Enid Bakewell]]\n* [[Jan Brittin]]\n* [[Jacqueline Court]]\n* [[Rachel Heyhoe Flint]]\n* [[Carole Hodges]]\n* [[Shirley Hodges]]\n* [[Glynis Hullah]]\n* [[Megan Lear]]\n* [[Jan Southgate]]\n* [[Avril Starling]]\n* [[Helen Stother]]\n* [[Janet Tedstone]]\n* [[Chris Watmough]]\n|valign=top|\n* [[Shantha Rangaswamy]] ([[Captain (cricket)|c]])\n* [[Mangal Babar]]\n* [[Gargi Banerji]]\n* [[Vrinda Bhagat]]\n* [[Lopamudra Bhattacharj]]\n* [[Sharmila Chakraborty]]\n* [[Rajeshwari Dholakia]]\n* [[Diana Edulji]]\n* [[Nilima Jogalekar]]\n* [[Fowzieh Khalili]]\n* [[Shubhangi Kulkarni]]\n* [[Anjali Pendharker]]\n* [[Manjoo Sharma]]\n* [[Sujata Sridhar]]\n|-\n! width=33% | [[File:Flag of None.svg|22px]] [[International XI women's cricket team|International XI]]<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Hansells_Vita_Fresh_Womens_World_Cup_1981-82/International_XI_Women_Batting.html Batting and fielding for International XI women], Hansells Vita Fresh Women's World Cup 1981/82 \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 29 August 2015.</ref>\n! width=33% | {{crw|NZL}}<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Hansells_Vita_Fresh_Womens_World_Cup_1981-82/New_Zealand_Women_Batting.html Batting and fielding for New Zealand women], Hansells Vita Fresh Women's World Cup 1981/82 \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 29 August 2015.</ref>\n! width=33%| \n|-\n|valign=top|\n* {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Lynne Thomas]] ([[Captain (cricket)|c]])\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[Sandra Braganza]]\n* {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Jan Hall (cricketer)|Jan Hall]]\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lynley Hamilton]]\n* {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Mary Harris (cricketer)|Mary Harris]]\n* {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Karen Jobling]]\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Rhonda Kendall]]\n* {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Gill McConway]]\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[Renuka Majumder]]\n* {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Chris Miller (cricketer)|Chris Miller]]\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Jenny Owens (cricketer)|Jenny Owens]]\n* {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Sue Rattray]]\n* {{flagicon|NED}} [[Ingrid van der Elst]]\n* {{flagicon|NED}} [[Babette van Teunenbroek]]\n|valign=top|\n* [[Trish McKelvey]] ([[Captain (cricket)|c]])\n* [[Eileen Badham]]\n* [[Barbara Bevege]]\n* [[Sue Brown (cricketer)|Sue Brown]]\n* [[Vicki Burtt]]\n* [[Linda Fraser]]\n* [[Debbie Hockley]]\n* [[Jackie Lord]]\n* [[Carol Marett]]\n* [[Lesley Murdoch]]\n* [[Maureen Peters (cricketer)|Maureen Peters]]\n* [[Karen Plummer]]\n* [[Edna Ryan (cricketer)|Edna Ryan]]\n* [[Nicki Turner]]\n| \n|}\n\n==Venues==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ 1982 Women's Cricket World Cup venues\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | City\n! scope=\"col\" | Island\n! scope=\"col\" | Matches\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Map\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Eden Park]]\n| [[Auckland]] || North || 2 \n| rowspan=\"15\" | {{Location map+|New Zealand|width=350|float=center|caption=Venue locations within New Zealand\n|places=\n  {{Location map~|New Zealand|lat_deg=-36|lat_min=-50|lon_deg=174|lon_min=44|position=left|background=|label=[[Auckland]]|label_size=80}}\n  {{Location map~|New Zealand|lat_deg=-37|lat_min=-47|lon_deg=175|lon_min=17|position=left|background=|label=[[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]|label_size=80}}\n  {{Location map~|New Zealand|lat_deg=-39|lat_min=-04|lon_deg=174|lon_min=05|position=left|background=|label=[[New Plymouth]]|label_size=80}}\n  {{Location map~|New Zealand|lat_deg=-39|lat_min=-29