{"title_page": "Hermitage, Berkshire", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n|country = England\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.452536|-1.276217|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name= Hermitage\n|static_image_name= Large Garden Centre, Hermitage - geograph.org.uk - 11376.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Garden Centre\n| population = 1943\n|population_ref=([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]])<ref name=ons>[http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk Key Statistics: Dwellings; Quick Statistics: Population Density; Physical Environment: Land Use Survey 2005]</ref>\n|area_total_km2=6.36\n|civil_parish=  Hermitage\n|unitary_england= [[West Berkshire]]\n|region= South East England\n|lieutenancy_england = [[Berkshire]]\n|constituency_westminster=\n|post_town= NEWBURY\n|postcode_district = RG18\n|postcode_area= RG\n|dial_code= 01635\n|os_grid_reference= \n}}\n\n'''Hermitage''' is a village and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]], near to [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], in the [[England|English]] county of [[Berkshire]]. The civil parish is made up of a number of settlements: Hermitage village, Little Hungerford and Wellhouse.\n\n==Location==\nThe village is [[nucleated village|focussed residentially]] on the B4009, {{convert|5|mi|km}} north east of Newbury in the heart of the [[North Wessex Downs]], an [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]. It is thus surrounded by protected woodlands and undulating fields providing a few elevated viewpoints.\n\n==Transport==\n===Roads===\nAccess to the [[M4 motorway|M4]] is within 5 miles (and it also passes through the edge of the parish), which links [[Wales]] to [[London]], and the [[A34 road (England)|A34]] passes through the edge of the parish, a main transport artery from the north to the south of the United Kingdom.\n\n===Public transport===\nFrom 1882 until the 1960s the village had [[Hermitage railway station|a minor halt station]]. The station was erected by the [[Didcot, Newbury and Southampton Railway]], also the name of its line.  As of 18 February 2013, Hermitage is served by buses 6 and 6A from [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newburyanddistrict.co.uk/pdf/jan13/connect-service-6-and-6A-%28effective-from-18-Feb-2013%29.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=11 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819070346/http://newburyanddistrict.co.uk/pdf/jan13/connect-service-6-and-6A-(effective-from-18-Feb-2013).pdf |archive-date=19 August 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Amenities==\nIt has a general store and [[post office]], a [[Church of England parish church|church]] (Holy Trinity) and two [[public house]]s (The Fox and The White Horse of Hermitage). There is a large garden centre with a cafe, bonsai shop, pool & spa concession and lawnmower centre. The village [[primary school]] feeds into the Downs School. The area is predominantly agricultural and the main local employers are the village school, village pre-school, the [[garden centre]] and a small light industrial unit housing several small businesses.\n\nThe [[Royal School of Military Survey]] at [[Denison Barracks]] houses a small garrison of troops and their families. However, though generally referred to as being in Hermitage, it is actually just across the border in the [[Curridge]] area of [[Chieveley]] parish.\n\n==History==\nOn Oare Common are two curvilinear ditched enclosures which are probably of [[prehistory|prehistoric]] date, although it has also been suggested that they may represent a [[motte and bailey]] [[castle]]. The [[hill fort]] of [[Grimsbury Castle]] is in Grimsbury Wood. A [[folly]] stands at its centre. A 2nd and 3rd century [[Roman villa]] of some pretensions was discovered at Wellhouse in [[Victorian era|Victorian times]]. Between 1917 and 1918 [[D. H. Lawrence]] lived in Hermitage at Chapel Farm Cottage, Chapel Lane.<ref>[http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/mss/online/online-exhibitions/exhib_dhl/b7.phtml Online exhibitions - The University of Nottingham]. Nottingham.ac.uk. Retrieved on 2013-07-17.</ref> His novella [[The Fox (novella)|''The Fox'']] is set in the area, with Bailey Farm based on Grimsby Farm.<ref>Poplawski, Paul and Worthen, John. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sMVfuWKXX2EC&pg=PA336&lpg=PA336&dq=D+H+Lawrence+hermitage+the+fox&source=bl&ots=YH2xnStQ4L&sig=ACfU3U0bTXNAYO1vn009I8UNGPqFQmL6Iw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi9kOLpucfoAhWrQUEAHT7wChkQ6AEwBXoECAsQLw#v=onepage&q=D%20H%20Lawrence%20hermitage%20the%20fox&f=false ''D.H. Lawrence: A Reference Companion''] (1996), p 336</ref>\n of \n===Housing expansion===\nThree early 21st century housing areas were completed in the north and south. These include Forest Edge and Hermitage Green.\n\n==Demography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n|+ '''2011 Published Statistics: Population, home ownership and extracts from Physical Environment, surveyed in 2005<ref name=ons />'''\n|-\n!Output area||Homes owned outright||Owned with a loan||Socially rented||Privately rented||Other||Usual residents ||km\u00b2\n|- align=center\n|Civil parish||192||\t312\t||66\t||104\t||16\t||1943||\t6.36\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hermitage, Berkshire}}\n*[http://www.hermitage.org.uk Hermitage and Hermitage Parish Council Website]\n\n{{West Berkshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Berkshire]]\n[[Category:West Berkshire District]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Berkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n|country = England\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.452536|-1.276217|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name= Hermitage\n|static_image_name= Large Garden Centre, Hermitage - geograph.org.uk - 11376.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Garden Centre\n| population = 1943\n|population_ref=([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]])<ref name=ons>[http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk Key Statistics: Dwellings; Quick Statistics: Population Density; Physical Environment: Land Use Survey 2005]</ref>\n|area_total_km2=6.36\n|civil_parish=  Hermitage\n|unitary_england= [[West Berkshire]]\n|region= South East England\n|lieutenancy_england = [[Berkshire]]\n|constituency_westminster=\n|post_town= NEWBURY\n|postcode_district = RG18\n|postcode_area= RG\n|dial_code= 01635\n|os_grid_reference= \n}}\n\n'''Hermitage''' is a village and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]], near to [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], in the [[England|English]] county of [[Berkshire]]. The civil parish is made up of a number of settlements: Hermitage village, Little Hungerford and Wellhouse.\n\n==Location==\nThe village is [[nucleated village|focussed residentially]] on the B4009, {{convert|5|mi|km}} north east of Newbury in the heart of the [[North Wessex Downs]], an [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]. It is thus surrounded by protected woodlands and undulating fields providing a few elevated viewpoints.\n\n==Transport==\n===Roads===\nAccess to the [[M4 motorway|M4]] is within 5 miles (and it also passes through the edge of the parish), which links [[Wales]] to [[London]], and the [[A34 road (England)|A34]] passes through the edge of the parish, a main transport artery from the north to the south of the United Kingdom.\n\n===Public transport===\nFrom 1882 until the 1960s the village had [[Hermitage railway station|a minor halt station]]. The station was erected by the [[Didcot, Newbury and Southampton Railway]], also the name of its line.  As of 18 February 2013, Hermitage is served by buses 6 and 6A from [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newburyanddistrict.co.uk/pdf/jan13/connect-service-6-and-6A-%28effective-from-18-Feb-2013%29.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=11 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819070346/http://newburyanddistrict.co.uk/pdf/jan13/connect-service-6-and-6A-(effective-from-18-Feb-2013).pdf |archive-date=19 August 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Amenities==\nIt has a general store and [[post office]], a [[Church of England parish church|church]] (Holy Trinity) and two [[public house]]s (The Fox and The White Horse of Hermitage). There is a large garden centre with a cafe, bonsai shop, pool & spa concession and lawnmower centre. The village [[primary school]] feeds into the Downs School. The area is predominantly agricultural and the main local employers are the village school, village pre-school, the [[garden centre]] and a small light industrial unit housing several small businesses.\n\nThe [[Royal School of Military Survey]] at [[Denison Barracks]] houses a small garrison of troops and their families. However, though generally referred to as being in Hermitage, it is actually just across the border in the [[Curridge]] area of [[Chieveley]] parish.\n\n==History==\nOn Oare Common are two curvilinear ditched enclosures which are probably of [[prehistory|prehistoric]] date, although it has also been suggested that they may represent a [[motte and bailey]] [[castle]]. The [[hill fort]] of [[Grimsbury Castle]] is in Grimsbury Wood. A [[folly]] stands at its centre. A 2nd and 3rd century [[Roman villa]] of some pretensions was discovered at Wellhouse in [[Victorian era|Victorian times]]. Between 1917 and 1918 [[D. H. Lawrence]] lived in Hermitage.<ref>[http://www.nottingham.ac.uk/mss/online/online-exhibitions/exhib_dhl/b7.phtml Online exhibitions - The University of Nottingham]. Nottingham.ac.uk. Retrieved on 2013-07-17.</ref>\n\n===Housing expansion===\nThree early 21st century housing areas were completed in the north and south. These include Forest Edge and Hermitage Green.\n\n==Demography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n|+ '''2011 Published Statistics: Population, home ownership and extracts from Physical Environment, surveyed in 2005<ref name=ons />'''\n|-\n!Output area||Homes owned outright||Owned with a loan||Socially rented||Privately rented||Other||Usual residents ||km\u00b2\n|- align=center\n|Civil parish||192||\t312\t||66\t||104\t||16\t||1943