{"title_page": "David Secher", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2015}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=November 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''David Secher''' is a specialist in research commercialisation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Programme Committee: David Secher |url=http://www.praxiscourses.org.uk/about/dsecher.asp |work=PraxisUnico: Commercialising research |accessdate=7 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717180655/http://www.praxiscourses.org.uk/about/dsecher.asp |archivedate=17 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>  He was awarded the [[Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion (2007)|Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion]] in 2007 for his work as the co-founder and Chairman of Praxis (now [[PraxisAuril]],<ref>{{cite web|title=PraxisAuril|url=http://www.praxisauril.org.uk}}</ref> of which he is now Patron) and the first chief executive of the [[N8 Group]], a group of universities in the north of England. He is now the Principal of Cambridge Knowledge Transfer (a KT and Interim Management consultancy company); and a Life Fellow of [[Gonville and Caius College]], Cambridge.  He is also a non-executive director of Crossword Cybersecurity plc and the Chair of Fitzwilliam Museum Enterprises Ltd.  He is an elected member of the University of Cambridge Finance Committee.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Secher, David}}\n[[Category:Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion (2007)]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{UK-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2015}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=November 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''David Secher''' is a specialist in research commercialisation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Programme Committee: David Secher |url=http://www.praxiscourses.org.uk/about/dsecher.asp |work=PraxisUnico: Commercialising research |accessdate=7 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717180655/http://www.praxiscourses.org.uk/about/dsecher.asp |archivedate=17 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>  He was awarded the [[Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion (2007)|Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion]] in 2007 for his work as the co-founder and Chairman of Praxis (now [[PraxisAuril]],<ref>{{cite web|title=PraxisAuril|url=http://www.praxisauril.org.uk}}</ref> of which he is now Patron) and the first chief executive of the [[N8 Group]], a group of universities in the north of England. He is now the Principal of Cambridge Knowledge Transfer (a KT and Interim Management consultancy company); and a Life Fellow of [[Gonville and Caius College]], Cambridge.  He is also a non-executive director of Crossword Cybersecurity plc and the Chair of Fitzwilliam Museum Enterprises Ltd.  He is an elected member of the University of Cambridge Finance Committee.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Secher, David}}\n[[Category:Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion (2007)]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{UK-business-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Secher"}
